Move bandit into the linters blacklist

It is similar to flake8 a generic static code linter
and not necessary for building a binary distribution
of OpenStack, so enforcing a g-r consistent version
seems to be slightly over the top

commit_message:
Add project-template for functional tips jobs

Rather than adding them individual in other places, make a functional
tips project-template.

Name it shade-functional-tips rather than shade-functional-devstack-tips
because we might add jobs like shade-functional-ansible-tips or
something in the future and might want to include such things.

Change-Id: I544fdf515f8df38d73cee64a6de799ab384a326e

- gate-nova-specs-python27-ubuntu-xenial http://logs.openstack.org/65/497965/2/check/gate-nova-specs-python27-ubuntu-xenial/12e2231/ : SUCCESS in 3m 25s'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2017-08-26 10:09:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(11 comments)

Some good ideas in here, Eric, thank you! Also, some pretty good explanation of the existing problems that exist in the device management arena.

I left a variety of comments inline, but I'll leave my big comment here in the top-level review...

I have some serious reservations (no pun intended) about attempting to hack the existing PCI device management subsystem any further than it already has been hacked.

With the advent of the resource provider modeling, which includes an appropriate modeling of quantitative and qualitative things split out into resources (with inventory and allocation) and traits, we have a system that can (and IMHO should) be the basis for any future improvements to device management in Nova.

Instead of attempting to hack the existing PCI manager (specifically the device pool functionality) to group on things other than product_id and vendor_id, I would support moving towards a new generic device manager subsystem, written from scratch with none of the existing PCI module code.

This new device manager subsystem would use the resource provider modeling and track inventory and allocations in the placement API. It would be agnostic to the underlying hypervisor and communicate with the placement API and the virt driver. It would use UUIDs to identify specific devices on a host (or host-like thing in the case of PowerVM).

The virt driver would be responsible for maintaining a mapping of UUID to whatever internal string or numeric identifier it uses to uniquely identify a device. The virt driver, in coordination with the hypervisor, would also be responsible for querying the inventory of devices available on the host (as they currently are). However, instead of passing a dict of randomness back to the resource tracker in the get_available_resource() method, instead, the virt driver would work with the device manager in constructing a tree of resource providers, build inventories for those resource providers, and associate standard and custom traits to those resource providers. Once this is done, allocation/claiming will be done via the scheduler just like any other resource in the system.

Best,

-jay"}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2017-08-26 12:43:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

Great start Eric.

While I agree with jay that the ideal is a "new device manager subsystem" it may be that advancing both ideas concurrently will be useful as they will each inform the other. Also, unless I've misunderstood, part of the purpose of the whiteisting is to allow static configuration on a specific piece of hardware of what resources it exposes. That mechanism, or something like it, will still need to exist when the virt driver is generating the tree of nested providers.

Token -1 to ack that I've noticed, yeah, this is not yet done.'}, {'account_id': 14070, 'date': '2017-08-26 15:50:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

(7 comments)

Guys, thanks a ton for the feedback.

I totally agree a full rewrite with generic resource providers is the way to go long term.  I even filed a blueprint [1] at the same time as this one (spec not started).  Is that achievable for Queens?

Also, even when we have the RP nirvana, we'll still need some form of whitelisting capability (so Ophelia can limit the devices available to Endymion).  What does the rewrite of that look like, and more to the point, how do we transition from the existing setup?  That'll be a pretty weird deprecation changeover.

[1] https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/devices-as-resources"}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2017-08-28 08:03:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Guys, please note that I am not advocating rewriting the PCI manager code. I am talking about creating a *new* generic device manager that would live alongside the existing PCI manager. The existing PCI manager code would continue to work for virt drivers that have not yet been updated to work with the new generic device manager.

So, the general plan would be:

1) Write the generic device manager (let's call this the GDM) as an entirely new module. this module would be the bridge between the virt driver and the placement API. The GDM's southbound interface (to the virt driver) would pass a ProviderTree object [1] to the virt driver via a new virt driver API method called update_device_info() [2]. The virt driver would be responsible for discovering all devices usable for a host and adding/updating/deleting providers from the supplied provider tree. Note that no usage information is present in the provider tree, only inventory and traits information. Also note that the provider tree doesn't care about things like device addresses, device bus or type.

If the virt driver wants to use the pci_passthrough_whitelist for filtering devices, it can feel free to do so. If the virt driver wants to read a YAML file of device information that is specific to the underlying host architecture, it can do so. If the virt driver wants to read information from some local filesystem, it can do so. The GDM doesn't care.

2) Once the virt driver has updated the ProviderTree passed to it by the GDM in the update_device_info() method, the GDM is then responsible for reading through that ProviderTree and calling the methods on the SchedulerReportClient for updating inventory and trait information as needed.

3) We would need some marker service version to indicate the time when all compute nodes had been updated to use the GDM for device resource management. Similar to how we did the tests for deployments containing Ocata computes when working the edge scenarios for move operations in late Pike around claims in the scheduler. The GDM, in parallel to the regular PCI device manager, would add inventory records for resource providers but until the marker service version is reached, the set of resources and traits passed to the placement API by the scheduler would not include resources like SRIOV_NET_VF. Similarly, the PciRequest object that is currently constructed by looking at port profile information from Neutron would need to continue to be constructed until the marker service version is attained and a set of standard resource classes and traits (built from the port profile information) can be added to the request that the scheduler sends to placement. This will effectively mean that the PciPassthroughFilter filter would be redundant and could be removed.

Anyway, just a brain dump on this Monday... lots to talk about in Denver.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/compute/provider_tree.py#L77
[2] names suck. feel free to suggest a better one."}, {'account_id': 8864, 'date': '2017-08-31 15:55:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

You guys want to take a look at [1]? It seems related, and I thought Jay's comment from here should apply there as well. Maybe work together with Maciej and come up with One Spec to Rule Them All?

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/474218/"}, {'account_id': 8213, 'date': '2017-09-11 11:54:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(5 comments)'}, {'account_id': 8213, 'date': '2017-09-11 11:57:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I still have to read the rest of the spec, but I do agree that the PCI resource allocation needs some rework. At the moment, Hyper-V SR-IOV support cannot be added without some of these changes. :)'}, {'account_id': 22255, 'date': '2017-10-09 07:28:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

Thanks for your patch, I have some suggestions bellow'}, {'account_id': 14070, 'date': '2017-10-25 22:35:13.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

No more messing with the PCI subsystem.  Let's do this right, with generic device management."}]

commit_message:
RFC: SPEC: PCI passthrough by device ID

Not all devices have a vendor ID and product ID. Not all hypervisors
address devices in domain:slot:bus.func format. And it would be nice to
be able to group devices at a granularity other than product/vendor ID
for the purpose of identifying them in a flavor for attachment to a VM.

This work aims to support identifying PCI devices in the
[pci]passthrough_whitelist, the [pci]alias list, and the
pci_passthrough_devices list (provided by the compute driver’s
get_available_resource) via an arbitrary device_id string. As a
baseline, device_id strings will be matched exactly for purposes of
whitelist filtering and claiming. As a stretch goal, a hook will be
provided allowing the compute driver to perform matching in whatever way
it deems appropriate.

NOTE: This spec is in a request-for-comments state, replete through the
Proposed Change section.  Requesting feedback before moving forward with
implementation details.

Change-Id: Icd7989cff12d3333c4d7ca8019e7c3643554b884
Implements: bp pci-by-device-id

wrt ironic CLI. We have a msg: "You are using the default API version of the 'ironic' command. This is currently API version 1.9. In the future, the default will be the latest API version understood by both API and CLI. You can preserve the current behavior by passing the --ironic-api-version argument with the desired version or using the IRONIC_API_VERSION environment variable."

So we should decide if we are going to change it for that too. Whatever we do, we should update that warning :)'}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2017-10-23 15:22:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

I'm still testing, but wrt my comments, I think we need to make clear in the release notes, what is going on. Spell out what/if anything changes with ironic CLI & python API.

The others are nits."}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2017-10-23 15:24:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

OH, sorry, I'd like to see a 'features' in the reno too. For those that aren't upgrading,  they might not read that part."}, {'account_id': 11655, 'date': '2017-10-23 15:28:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2017-10-23 15:33:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2017-10-23 15:46:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2017-10-23 15:52:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

tested, looks good!'}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2017-10-23 16:17:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

I took a look at the spec [1]. We're missing this:
"If only the major version is specified (for example, --os-baremetal-api-version=1), the latest compatible version of that major version will be used (e.g. 1.32 if that’s the latest 1.XX version)."

[1] http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/ironic-specs/specs/not-implemented/cli-default-api-version.html#proposed-change'}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2017-10-23 20:39:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

wrt "If only the major version is specified (for example, --os-baremetal-api-version=1)...". I tested this ("openstack baremetal port group list --os-baremetal-api-version 1), and got "EndpointNotFound: Could not find requested endpoint in Service Catalog."

I'm fine if we pull/put this into a separate RFE, and/or just fix it in another client release, since it doesn't default to 1.9 anyway. I'm not sure what it should do -- does the API WG have a recommendation?'}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2017-10-23 20:58:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

wrt what to do with Ironic CLI. From meeting, Dmitry suggested these choices: 1. remove the warning about the version change, 2. change the default version

I took a look at the changes in the next client release. Here's my thinking:
- since/if we deprecate ironic CLI and make this change in the same release, it sort of makes sense to also make the same change to ironic, so that they are 'the same' at the time of deprecating the ironic CLI.
- it would certainly be less work to remove the warning and leave the default version as 1.9, although we are going to still have ironic CLI until s* cycle, so we'd need to remember the diffs between the two CLIs. I think if we want to do this, I would prefer if we push out a release with the ironic CLI deprecation (to signify we're deprecating, they are both compatible at this point); then push out another release with this change to OSC. If we did that, would both releases need to be major releases (and if so, does it even matter?) [I am going to try to stop thinking about this now :) ]"}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2017-10-24 14:10:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Workflow-1

commit_message:
Set the default API version of OSC CLI to "latest"

Now the default of OSC is the negotiated maximum version understood
by both the server and the client. The value of "1" is now equivalent
to "latest" as well.

This change also cleans up unit tests for the OSC plugin.

Change-Id: I489fee937a356b523eb35379dce3631195132fe5
Closes-Bug: #1671145

[{'created': '2017-10-24 16:25:50.000000000', 'message': "[upstream] Add Stable Release info to Release Cycle Slides

During the Boston Summit education session there were
questions about stable branches during the 'Release Cycle'
presentation.  We decided it would be good to add slides for
this to that presentation.

This patch adds those slides.  Also, it appears that the way
that ReST is processed by the latest tooling is slightly different.
If you don't have spaces before and after an indented section it
doesn't indent the bullets.  This patch fixes that for this
set of slides as well.

Change-Id: I9981f661f4a82b4b4c9a5591f88d5039a3671fc4

commit_message:
[upstream] Add Stable Release info to Release Cycle Slides

During the Boston Summit education session there were
questions about stable branches during the 'Release Cycle'
presentation.  We decided it would be good to add slides for
this to that presentation.

This patch adds those slides.  Also, it appears that the way
that ReST is processed by the latest tooling is slightly different.
If you don't have spaces before and after an indented section it
doesn't indent the bullets.  This patch fixes that for this
set of slides as well.

There was also some awkward wording that was caught in review.
This fixes those issues as well.

Change-Id: I9981f661f4a82b4b4c9a5591f88d5039a3671fc4

commit_message:
Use ANSIBLE_HOST_KEY_CHECKING var instead of ssh-common-args

ssh-common-args get ignored in ansible 2.4 due to
https://github.com/ansible/ansible/issues/30720
This change adds the use of ANSIBLE_HOST_KEY_CHECKING env var as
a replacement for the ssh-common-args cli option.

Closes-bug: 1725224

Change-Id: I398e93d57f6155b59c3f049558558b3a18f4762c

this especially removes stable/newton matches but also some driverfixes
and mitaka ones on projects that don't have these branches.

commit_message:
Run gerrit periodic on openstack/2.13 only

We have several openstack/2.13 branches, the v2 job run only on exactly
one - the openstack/2.13 one. Let's run the new ones on exactly the same
branch.

Note that branches is a regex, see
https://docs.openstack.org/infra/zuul/feature/zuulv3/user/config.html#attr-job.branches
So, we need to add ^ and $ to be explicit and avoid match against
openstrack/2.13.3 and similar named branches.

Change-Id: I88fb6d5e7df1739724901b661a9365c30582913c

commit_message:
Do not try and iterate [None] in l3-agent network_update()

Since ri.ex_gw_port can be None, the l3-agent can throw an
exception when looking for ports it might have in a given
network.

(cherry picked from 2cea213d94e3ac7675d62491cec6c85253285b92)

Change-Id: I3ab3e9c012022cd7eefa5c609ca9540649079ad3
Closes-bug: #1724043

subject: Enhance test case fail to build  message
revisions:
[{'created': '2017-10-23 18:07:28.000000000', 'message': "Enhance test case fail to build  message

When instances fail to build successfully during the gate runs
it is common to see a KeyError on 'ip'.  This is coming from the
test_runner code which is expecting the instance to have an IP
address.

This puts a check on 'ip' before its usage and fails the tests
with an more explicit error message.

Change-Id: Ibd926e90190024a5b1979b3a09fa1eda12aa7106
"}]
commit_message:
Enhance test case fail to build  message

When instances fail to build successfully during the gate runs
it is common to see a KeyError on 'ip'.  This is coming from the
test_runner code which is expecting the instance to have an IP
address.

This puts a check on 'ip' before its usage and fails the tests
with an more explicit error message.

Change-Id: Ibd926e90190024a5b1979b3a09fa1eda12aa7106

commit_message:
Adds checking proxy server before using it.

The previous proxy code in rhel-registration did not test the
proxy itself before use. This consequence was that the overcloud
would deploy properly even if the proxy was not reachable/useable.

This change tests that the RHSM portal is reachable and useable
through the configured proxy server. It aborts the deployment
if the proxy is not reachable or if it is not capable of reaching
out to RHSM using curl to http://subscription.rhsm.redhat.com.

Change-Id: I2e2d853674499b179d05e998f9e37dc8d8f8bb23

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-10-25 20:04:46.000000000', 'message': 'Delete containers created in tests only

In before, tempest tests will delete all containers on teardown.
This is problematic if concurrency is set larger than 1 since there
would be some race conditions when multiple processes are trying
to do the cleanup.

This patch proposes to record the list of containers created in
tests and cleanup those containers only.

Change-Id: I0823fbbf999f346f08d283b76073a6da461bb9e3
'}]
commit_message:
Delete containers created in tests only

In before, tempest tests will delete all containers on teardown.
This is problematic if concurrency is set larger than 1 since there
would be some race conditions when multiple processes are trying
to do the cleanup.

This patch proposes to record the list of containers created in
tests and cleanup those containers only.

Change-Id: I0823fbbf999f346f08d283b76073a6da461bb9e3

commit_message:
Disable voting on 2 multinode tripleo jobs

scenario001 and 004 are timeouting too much when deploying with
containers.
We're investigating why but in the meantime let's disable voting for
now.

Change-Id: I25e7113d6ef8efdd69ce507ea32adbbeca451e4e

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-05-16 12:42:03.000000000', 'message': "[WIP] Driver changes for TAP SF support in portchain

SFC, by default supports port-chain for SFs inserted in L3 mode.
There are deployments which requires SFs to be inserted in TAP mode
which are used for network traffic monitoring.

Now, TAP SF can be inserted in port-chain by creating
port-pair-group with port-group-parameters 'tap_enabled'
set to True.

Multiple port-pairs in tap_enabled PPG will be done later in
another commit.

Consecutive TAP PPG insertion in port-chain is not supported now.

Change-Id: I76e38764e81b4632ad7b0a58d0b13600d5a1e7be
Partially-Implements: blueprint SFC Port-pair Tap

commit_message:
Driver changes for Tap SF support in portchain

SFC, by default supports port-chain for SFs inserted in L3 mode.
There are deployments which requires SFs to be inserted in Tap mode
which are used for network traffic monitoring.

Now, Tap SF can be inserted in port-chain by creating
port-pair-group with '--enable-tap' flag set to True.

Multiple port-pairs in tap enabled PPG will be done later in
another commit.

Consecutive Tap PPG insertion in port-chain is not supported now.

Change-Id: I76e38764e81b4632ad7b0a58d0b13600d5a1e7be
Partially-Implements: blueprint sfc-tap-port-pair

commit_message:
Use assertIsNone(...) instead of assertIs(None,...)

Following OpenStack Style Guidelines: [1]
Unit test assertions tend to give better messages for more
specific assertions. As a result, assertIsNone(...) is
preferred over assertIs(None, ...)

[1] http://docs.openstack.org/developer/hacking/#unit-tests-and-assertraises

Change-Id: Ie4ee3be201f799d87c06378cd2c9a0a3c34c24df

commit_message:
Enable qos and trunk service_plugins

Review [1] added some tests which requires "qos" and "trunk"
plugins to be enabled, so add it to the neutron plugins_list.

Also add "qos" to extension_drivers.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/479995/

Change-Id: I64fe3e1853b6e7f0b5755dad191da9a5b04e307e

commit_message:
Correct regex for disk size

Currently the regex negates any line starting with
any character in the word 'Filesystem', whereas the
intent is to negate the word 'Filesystem' instead.

Closes-Bug: #1724025
Change-Id: Ia40595e3a06a23494165a210e1dd3e72862eb311
(cherry picked from commit 3ce37a347adb343fe6f493724b22c4846a1163a1)

commit_message:
Don't ignore nova/tests for the live-migration jobs

While attemping to test a change to our live migration test hook [1],
we noticed that zuul is excluding our hook file for running our live
migration jobs.

It looks like it was a regression during the move to zuul v3 [2].

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/508163
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/507180/11/zuul/layout.yaml@a2453

Change-Id: Ie78f6f0f2b349f44a896aedac8cdf66358a7ff5c

the security hardning playbook to the defeault re-deployment process. If

'}]
commit_message:
Run security hardening when leaping a deployment

The security hardening playbook was not being executed. This change adds
the security hardning playbook to the defeault re-deployment process. If
a deployer wishes to opt-out of the default security hardening they can
disable it using the `apply_security_hardening` option.

Change-Id: I69baa1d2cb209cf3686ca2da00e698ed5dbf92f9
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Fix ceph incremental backup fail

Cinder _rbd_diff_transfer() uses "import-diff" and "export-diff" cmdline
to do a incremental backup, it will fail without a ceph-conf file. Delay
to delete temporary ceph-conf file in class RBDConnector during ceph
volume backup.

Change-Id: Ib74c85266b8c812f7a40dac293847a28768eae9a
Partial-Bug: #1578036
(cherry picked from commit 1fe844efaf324ed7b9b64c21f1c3f8af9f616738)

commit_message:
Remove the parameter enforce_type from set_override and set_default

It's no longer possible to assign a value of a different type in the
config via an override. This behavior was changed in the last release to
default to disallow overrides of different types, and in this release it
is no longer able to be overridden

Change-Id: I8a5e868e0adc2c7b6f46f56ee77a8129c34badb9

commit_message:
Add I202 to flake ignore list

Pep8 job currently fails complaining about I202 in a bunch of
modules. This change fixes the genuine errors in the module
import order, and adds I202 to the skip list so that we don't
have to add noqa comments everywhere we can not satisfy the
check. After we split out the tempest plugin, we'll remove
I202 from the ignore list and add noqa comments in the places
where it will still be needed.

Change-Id: Ia170a41d35dea8c9eda2b36c907dbc518169a824

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-10-25 10:12:28.000000000', 'message': "Invoke AuthHook before ContextHook

Now in Mistral there is an AuthHook that should work for both Keystone
and Keycloak. But for Keystone the real call to the server is performed
earlier, in access_control [1], and AuthHook just contains a small check
of X-Identity-Status header, that was injected before.

Therefore, the sequence for Keystone auth is next:
1. Call Keystone auth middleware during access control check and inject
   required headers in the request object.
2. Call ContextHook and build the context.
3. Call Keystone AuthHook and validate X-Identity-Status header we got
   on step 1. [2]

Because of such a blurry logic, it seems that everything works as it
should.
But for Keycloak we honestly do autorization in AuthHook (where it
supposed to be), and we have the following sequence of actions:

1. Build an empty context without project_id and roles using ContextHook.
2. Call AuthHook and perform the authorization. [3]

So, even if the authorization was good and the headers were injected,
the context had already been created.

To fix this bug it's enough just to swap the order of calling the hooks,
because this is logical to build user context after authorization
process, because AuthHook may add new identity headers which can be
requred for the context builder.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/mistral/blob/master/mistral/api/access_control.py#L39
[2] https://github.com/openstack/mistral/blob/master/mistral/auth/keystone.py#L33-L35
[3] https://github.com/openstack/mistral/blob/master/mistral/auth/keycloak.py#L81

Change-Id: I33ae6ddfe2a62851401305ff1dd8890b6937e842
Closes-bug: #1719819
(cherry picked from commit 75e66117f049e00ba682f1d8977cdaa6eae35ef0)
"}]
commit_message:
Invoke AuthHook before ContextHook

Now in Mistral there is an AuthHook that should work for both Keystone
and Keycloak. But for Keystone the real call to the server is performed
earlier, in access_control [1], and AuthHook just contains a small check
of X-Identity-Status header, that was injected before.

Therefore, the sequence for Keystone auth is next:
1. Call Keystone auth middleware during access control check and inject
   required headers in the request object.
2. Call ContextHook and build the context.
3. Call Keystone AuthHook and validate X-Identity-Status header we got
   on step 1. [2]

Because of such a blurry logic, it seems that everything works as it
should.
But for Keycloak we honestly do autorization in AuthHook (where it
supposed to be), and we have the following sequence of actions:

1. Build an empty context without project_id and roles using ContextHook.
2. Call AuthHook and perform the authorization. [3]

So, even if the authorization was good and the headers were injected,
the context had already been created.

To fix this bug it's enough just to swap the order of calling the hooks,
because this is logical to build user context after authorization
process, because AuthHook may add new identity headers which can be
requred for the context builder.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/mistral/blob/master/mistral/api/access_control.py#L39
[2] https://github.com/openstack/mistral/blob/master/mistral/auth/keystone.py#L33-L35
[3] https://github.com/openstack/mistral/blob/master/mistral/auth/keycloak.py#L81

Change-Id: I33ae6ddfe2a62851401305ff1dd8890b6937e842
Closes-bug: #1719819
(cherry picked from commit 75e66117f049e00ba682f1d8977cdaa6eae35ef0)

commit_message:
Add handling of floating ip disassociation

When a compute port is deleted, neutron does not raise an event, so we
have to add explicit handling for this case is case a floating ip is
associated with that port.

Change-Id: Ifecc8f1635b5ca8af07df1c51d64c3174343531d
Closes-Bug: #1726693

intent is to negate the word 'Filesystem' instead.

commit_message:
Update number of workers to optimize gate memory

This change reduces the number of workers and
tweaks some Galera settings to better optimize
gate memory in newton.  It backports the values
relevent to newton from the original commit here:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/491641/

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-10-17 15:00:00.000000000', 'message': 'Add ceph-ansible v3 support

ceph-ansible has undergone significant refactoring in their v3
development, adding new required roles such as ceph-defaults and
ceph-config, which are used to provide vars and configuration to
the ceph service roles. These roles must be executed before the
service roles to avoid missing vars[1][2].

During the v3 refactoring, ceph-common was removed as a galaxy-style
role dependency in the service roles meta files[3]. This means we
will need to explicitly execute ceph-common from now on also.

This change adds the defaults and config roles and executes them.
Also some minor cleanup such as alphabetizing the OpenStack roles
list is done.

Also added is an upgrade playbook, reno, and docs to assist in
cleaning up the older galaxy-named ceph common roles which are
no longer galaxy namespaced in our cloning configuration.

commit_message:
Add ceph-ansible v3 support

ceph-ansible has undergone significant refactoring in their v3
development, adding new required roles such as ceph-defaults and
ceph-config, which are used to provide vars and configuration to
the ceph service roles. These roles must be executed before the
service roles to avoid missing vars[1][2].

During the v3 refactoring, ceph-common was removed as a galaxy-style
role dependency in the service roles meta files[3]. This means we
will need to explicitly execute ceph-common from now on also.

This change adds the defaults and config roles and executes them.
Also some minor cleanup such as alphabetizing the OpenStack roles
list is done.

Also added is an upgrade playbook, reno, and docs to assist in
cleaning up the older galaxy-named ceph common roles which are
no longer galaxy namespaced in our cloning configuration.

[1] http://jenkins-logs.objects-us-dfw-1.cloud.lstn.net/osa-ci/490192/1/21/logs/console.log
[2] https://github.com/ceph/ceph-ansible/issues/1737
[3] https://github.com/ceph/ceph-ansible/pull/1727

Conflicts:
  ansible-role-requirements.yml

Change-Id: Ia8c0cb0a23f331fce7914afbfc05ef54ee3ffb0e
(cherry picked from commit a53f1aea96096c10561edfb1626b56f433d5b58e)

Native DevStack jobs

Convert legacy DevStack jobs to native Zuul v3 form, plus some
test-job-related docs updates.

 > Couple suggestions about using DocumentedRuleDefault. Otherwise

commit_message:
Use non-pypi for release instead of tarball-only

The publish-openstack-python-tarball job is intended for use in
updating branch-tip snapshot builds. Python projects which will tag
releases should use release-openstack-python-without-pypi in
pre-release and release pipelines instead so that they get proper
artifact signatures uploaded to tarballs.openstack.org.

Change-Id: Ibdf687344df344b75c70ea74f64db3f36b576029

commit_message:
Add a Python release job for API services

OpenStack API services traditionally haven't published releases on
PyPI, but still want to follow all the other basic steps of the
release process aside from that (including tarball signing, release
announcements and so on). Add a specific job for this so we can
create a new project-template in a subsequent change to apply to
those projects.

Change-Id: I59b7b0af47a39ed8af599a162d8f80d7c2e5b187

messages: [{'account_id': 6816, 'date': '2017-10-24 15:55:25.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 7353, 'date': '2017-10-24 17:58:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 538, 'date': '2017-10-25 15:27:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow+1 Code-Review+2'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2017-10-24 15:55:25.000000000', 'message': "Remove unified queue from gate pipeline

Initially the intent for adding this was to better test
any patches for roles together before they merge, but it
has had the unintended side-effect of causing patches to
take much longer to merge (because they all get lined up
in a single queue, rather than independent queues) and
a lot more infra resources are used (because a patch
that fails at the top of the queue will result in all
subsequent patches restarting all their tests).

As discussed in the channel, we'd prefer to revert back
to the previous independent queue method of testing. It
has served us well.

Change-Id: I64b6728c0803de862e4183d7012eb1789ee8a846
"}]
commit_message:
Remove unified queue from gate pipeline

Initially the intent for adding this was to better test
any patches for roles together before they merge, but it
has had the unintended side-effect of causing patches to
take much longer to merge (because they all get lined up
in a single queue, rather than independent queues) and
a lot more infra resources are used (because a patch
that fails at the top of the queue will result in all
subsequent patches restarting all their tests).

As discussed in the channel, we'd prefer to revert back
to the previous independent queue method of testing. It
has served us well.

Change-Id: I64b6728c0803de862e4183d7012eb1789ee8a846

commit_message:
Update "always_run" to "check_mode"

always_run is deprecated. Use check_mode instead.
And this feature will be removed in version 2.4.

Change-Id: I7f2529a00538c1756e39cf644ed59b5dbd4bf7b5
Closes-Bug: #1677980

commit_message:
Remove tenant_id from compute endpoint

Since Nova API version 2.18, the tenant_id in the service catalog has
been optional (and recommended to not be used). This changes the
default installation instructions to not use it.

Change-Id: Ie8ad0829917bd36e0abb90869e2f1e8b4ca8cf10
See: Id92251243d9e92f30e466419110fce5781304823 for original change

messages:
[{'account_id': 22165, 'date': '2017-04-01 07:15:06.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 22165, 'date': '2017-04-01 07:19:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Published edit on patch set 1'}, {'account_id': 8157, 'date': '2017-04-01 07:24:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

Why removing init-runonce, it works great, it's simple...
your ansible doesn't generate output result in order to launch instance"}, {'account_id': 8157, 'date': '2017-04-01 07:25:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 22165, 'date': '2017-04-01 07:40:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> (1 comment)
 > 
 > Why removing init-runonce, it works great, it's simple...
 > your ansible doesn't generate output result in order to launch
 > instance

Ansible provided Openstack modules, we should use it, rather than  shell. The init-runone is not simple and have too much unnecessary command .

commit_message:
[WIP]Update the init openstack environment action

Since Ansible provided Openstack modules, the kolla-ansible should
use it, rather than the shell command. Besides that the init-runone
shell have too much unnecessary command. This patch update it.

Use "kolla-ansible init-runonce -i /path/all-in-one" to init OpenStack
environment.

Change-Id: I023cd76aa8a6840830a233dd7ca04274a40c465b

commit_message:
Add config parameter for nova config drive

Nova config drive can be used to pass parameters and files to the
database instances. In cases where file injection cannot be used
by nova, trove can be configured to tell nova to use config drive
support instead. Nova will then use config drive to configure the
database instance.

Change-Id: I29c1d0e935603a849c2500b2f298b7a6fa84cb28

commit_message:
Fix /etc/openstack-dashboard/ permissions for access to *policy.json

The Kolla Dockerfile sets the permissions for /etc/openstack-dashboard/
to horizon:horizon. We need this to be readable by the apache user
as the horizon user is not the user in which httpd runs with. We may
want to consider fixing this in the upstream Dockerfile instead, e.g.
checking if we're using centos/rhel and changing the permissions that
way. I'm not sure why it's set to horizon:horizon upstream, and I'm keen
not to break any existing functionality that relies on the horizon based
permissions.

Closes-Bug: #1723125
Change-Id: If5feebae38f7fdfffa60bfaedc4521f676006484

commit_message:
Enable convergence engine on the undercloud

We want to turn this on for Queens, and we might as well do it early
in the cycle so we have a chance to address any issues that may come
up.

We also want to migrate any existing stacks to use the convergence
engine to reduce the support matrix.  This patch includes a post-config
step do so.

Change-Id: I96952f78cb95252d2bc6c0df64561d07df51dc5a

commit_message:
Add cdm-scoping

This patch implements cdm-scoping.
Scoping yaml file is the following:

- compute:
  - availability_zones:
    - name: nova
  - host_aggregates:
    - id: 1
    - name: agg
  - exclude:
    - compute_nodes:
      - name: w012

Change-Id: I44e00218e90c5b08b397b2a9d7fed7c195f6dc55
Partially-Implements: blueprint cdm-scoping

Pep8 is the name for our linters target.'}, {'account_id': 12356, 'date': '2017-10-24 17:53:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

> you only run pep8 - which is correct. No need to run linters as
 > well.
 > 
 > do you want to say "run pep8 as linters jobs"? This is what you do.
 > 
 > Pep8 is the name for our linters target.

I was meant to add linters and pep8 as separate jobs, so that pep8 runs only doc8 command, and linters runs only testr (we do have a couple of unittests in our specs repo that validate rst). Andreas pointed out that this will be a waste of resources. Going back to pep8 only.'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2017-10-24 17:55:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Oh, you have tests - but those check titles. That's linting.

So, have one target - call it either linters or pep8 but don't use both, that would be just wasting resources."}, {'account_id': 12356, 'date': '2017-10-24 18:01:49.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 12356, 'date': '2017-10-24 18:03:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Run linters job instead of py27

py27 job ignores *.rst files, while the tests it runs actually check
those. Change it to linters instead.

Depends-On: Ib14c2a3318dc171be8c8ed8207524ab9774c5ccd
Change-Id: I49a549d6415b2daf64f0a168be5613788543b28b

commit_message:
Remove nodepool legacy jobs from project

These are now totally contained within the nodepool repo. Change ID
I42ee70ee08e4e7ea395d7a4f50061fcb4818913e removes the job definitions.
The zuul project also uses the in-repo version of the
nodepool-zuul-functional job.

Change-Id: Ibf893aaacfe7ec9ea82d829177cbc233516fcae9
Needed-By: I42ee70ee08e4e7ea395d7a4f50061fcb4818913e

commit_message:
lxc_cache_preparation: Convert the LXC cache preparation to async task

openSUSE sometimes hangs when running this task. In order to debug this
failure we need to fire up this task and check for it's status on a
separate one. This way, we can avoid Jenkins timeouts and collect logs
properly when that tasks fails to complete within a reasonable amount of
time.

Change-Id: I3acc4436c8b70af097de188b9de2bb9f4e093a09
(cherry picked from commit 025a800afc879bca32e08805e7b6e8201d23fdc0)

[{'created': '2017-10-24 16:42:10.000000000', 'message': 'Document reasonable radosgw timeout

The documented radosgw timeout of -1 can trigger

commit_message:
Document reasonable radosgw timeout

The documented radosgw timeout of -1 can trigger
cinder services to get stuck when experiencing any
Ceph/network related issue and does not allow for a
graceful recovery. A more reasonable value of 30
(seconds) is allowing for any connectivity releated
recovery.

Change-Id: I5f04254e77705c13cef165ea24fea3a45f2c20b1
Related-To: #1726936

commit_message:
Replace or_ with in_ function for searching queries

Now in several queries we use or_ to define filter conditions.
But it's known that in_ works faster [1], especially when filtering
occurs on non-indexed fields. Therefore it's suggested to replace
or_ with in_.

Local tests showed that the performance for such requests increases
to 30%, depending on the size of the database.

[1] https://stackoverflow.com/questions/782915/mysql-or-vs-in-performance

Change-Id: I47caf99b9b1a66713f9d92bca0d5f692b7f2a717

commit_message:
Remove remaining legacy openstack-ansible jobs

This removes the remaining legacy tests relating to
openstack-ansible repositories including the cross-repo
tests which were implemented for keystone, nova-lxd
and ARA.

The 'openstack-ansible' repo tests (both on-commit and
periodic) are being replaced by [1]. The cross-repo
tests will be re-implemented in a subsequent patch to
each repository using [2] in a similar fashion to
[3].

[1] https://review.openstack.org/513406
[2] https://review.openstack.org/513453
[3] https://review.openstack.org/513457

Change-Id: Id556ddae2146b36b5f3631ff461053d35e650276
Needed-By: I8fa8c0109a2047cbee789c50555cdc1d4f3dd268

commit_message:
Update manila tempest job skip conditions

Do not run manila-tempest-minimal-dsvm-lvm jobs for changes
that will not exercise it.  Also remove non-existent path
from the list of files triggering the skips.

Closes-Bug: #1720333

commit_message:
Allow containerized undercloud deploy with SELinux

When SELinux is enforcing, use :Z flag for the heat_all
container's volumes. Note, if a volume mount with a Z,
then the label will be specific to the container, and
not be able to be shared between containers.

Partial-bug: #1682179
Related-bug: #1723003

Change-Id: Ib4022e022eb2b757591635c362b572ab06f65ed8
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobreli@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Do not rely on openstack-puppet-modules in Queens and beyond

We are removing openstack-puppet-modules package since we now have
individual packages for each Puppet module.
We can still rely on puppet-tripleo module to deploy all dependencies.

Note: this patch will probably break undercloud-container on pike, but
this is fine as we target the feature for Queens, and the job is not
voting anyway.

Change-Id: I86a24516b457c81056942c903d020a5654142dc6
Related-Bug: #1676998

commit_message:
Use shim tool for dsvm functional test

Now individual tests can not be run using syntax like
"tox -e dsvm-functional TestOvnNbSyncOverTcp", all tests are run.
This patch fix it and only matched tests will be run.

Change-Id: I8c97544f9f5643d876685f86d98873488181e360
Signed-off-by: Dong Jun <dongj@dtdream.com>

commit_message:
Create Metadata port in OVN when found missing in Neutron

When running the neutron-ovn-db-sync-util tool and a Metadata port
is missing in Neutron, the corresponding LSP is not created in OVN.
This is due to the fact that OVN mechanism driver is overriden in the
cmd tool.

This patch fixes it by overriding the create_port_postcommit so that
it also gets created in OVN.

Closes-bug: 1724591

Change-Id: Iacb5f6eb3cecce883afae104764221d92f8ece04
Signed-off-by: Daniel Alvarez <dalvarez@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Remove wrapping of database exceptions in _get_collection()

* Method _get_collection() in api.py wraps all DB exceptions with
  DBQueryEntryError. It causes a problem because if it raises a
  DBDeadlock exception then it's not handled by @retry_on_deadlock
  decorator and the corresponding workflow operation gets lost.
  This patch remove this wrapping and also the exception class
  because it's not used anywhere else.

Closes-Bug: #1727152

Change-Id: If885bb63dc165aaf19001a4ff2c381732ee38982

commit_message:
Invoke AuthHook before ContextHook

Now in Mistral there is an AuthHook that should work for both Keystone
and Keycloak. But for Keystone the real call to the server is performed
earlier, in access_control [1], and AuthHook just contains a small check
of X-Identity-Status header, that was injected before.

Therefore, the sequence for Keystone auth is next:
1. Call Keystone auth middleware during access control check and inject
   required headers in the request object.
2. Call ContextHook and build the context.
3. Call Keystone AuthHook and validate X-Identity-Status header we got
   on step 1. [2]

Because of such a blurry logic, it seems that everything works as it
should.
But for Keycloak we honestly do autorization in AuthHook (where it
supposed to be), and we have the following sequence of actions:

1. Build an empty context without project_id and roles using ContextHook.
2. Call AuthHook and perform the authorization. [3]

So, even if the authorization was good and the headers were injected,
the context had already been created.

To fix this bug it's enough just to swap the order of calling the hooks,
because this is logical to build user context after authorization
process, because AuthHook may add new identity headers which can be
requred for the context builder.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/mistral/blob/master/mistral/api/access_control.py#L39
[2] https://github.com/openstack/mistral/blob/master/mistral/auth/keystone.py#L33-L35
[3] https://github.com/openstack/mistral/blob/master/mistral/auth/keycloak.py#L81

Change-Id: I33ae6ddfe2a62851401305ff1dd8890b6937e842
Closes-bug: #1719819

commit_message:
Make legacy-requirements-tox-validate-projects non-voting until fixed

The legacy-requirements-tox-validate-projects job is currently failing
because it is trying to validate the now removed Zuul v2 config.

Make it non-voting until it is fixed to verify the Zuul v3 config
properly instead.

Change-Id: I22f9ebf64eb1981e6421262e4ae43596d2b21043

"}, {'created': '2017-09-19 13:23:44.000000000', 'message': 'Switch to use stestr for unit tests directly

TrivialFix
In this change [1] os_testr changed under the covers from using
testr to stestr, so that we now get the following warning:
   ostestr.py:120:
   UserWarning: No .stestr.conf file found in the CWD.
   Please create one to to replace the .testr.conf. You can find a
   script to do this in the stestr git repository.

[1] Id7cb2a39a8308f1413608dcf19273a1d7f33592e
[2] https://media.readthedocs.org/pdf/stestr/stable/stestr.pdf
So remove the .testr.conf and add .stestr.conf which was
generated using a utility script as documented here [2].

Change-Id: I69a4e72a2d6411b1b596211569f212b04be30e51
'}, {'created': '2017-09-20 02:03:12.000000000', 'message': 'TrivialFix: Fix error ignore directory for git

doc/source/api should be generated docs, should not be
ignored, we should ignore doc/build directory stuff.

Change-Id: I69a4e72a2d6411b1b596211569f212b04be30e51
'}, {'created': '2017-09-25 05:16:12.000000000', 'message': 'TrivialFix: Fix error ignore directory in .gitignore

Previously, doc/source/api directory is ignored in .gitignore file,
this is not correct, because this directory is api docs, will generate
doc files, once the api docs changed, it will not submitted, so this
change is to open doc/source/api directory in .gitignore and close
doc/build.

Change-Id: I69a4e72a2d6411b1b596211569f212b04be30e51
'}, {'created': '2017-09-25 14:52:12.000000000', 'message': 'TrivialFix: Add doc/build directory in .gitignore

doc/build is generated directory, So we need to ignore it


Change-Id: I69a4e72a2d6411b1b596211569f212b04be30e51
'}]

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2016-11-02 13:32:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Ceph backup driver:delete the 'backup snapshot' for target volume

A snapshot will be generated when restoring backup to a volume if
cinder-volume and cinder-backup are ceph and diff restoring is
used. The snapshot is unnecessary when restore is complete. So
delete the 'backup snapshot' after diff restoring in
_diff_restore_rbd.

Change-Id: Ic120acd8767744a4ba5c07a31eb9915a6550b5c8

  underclouds as well.

  docker documentation as well.

  known master repos when deploying from stable releases.

commit_message:
Update containerized undercloud deployment guide

* Add a ref to undecloud installing steps for containerized
  underclouds as well.
* Add hints for reqiured repos configuration and official
  docker documentation as well.
* Add a warning for the repo config docs to not add last
  known master repos when deploying from stable releases.
* Add notes for required env vars to be exported/substituted.
* Add a step for the required host services to be started.
* Add a step for preparing containers images.

Related-bug: #1723003

Change-Id: Id358cbdf93c157a5be28e712ad80be5f46623678
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobreli@redhat.com>

Add option to enable or disable compute namespace for Ceilometer

In our beaker tests, we want to disable this as we do not have
any Nova dependencies.

Change-Id: I18b8e86217fb3bf9214946362e7910c30afa8196

Fixes a broken zanata-cli link

zanata-cli documentation link was changed after
zanata-client repository had been unified with zanata-platform.

More information: https://github.com/zanata/zanata-client

Replace deprecated library function os.popen() with subprocess

os.popen() is deprecated since python 2.6.
Resolved with use of subprocess module.

Change-Id: I8be4f420c42f73a7f57ad45010605b6a09a97e73
Closes-Bug: #1529836

commit_message:
Adds --overcloud-user option to upgrade-non-controller.sh

There is an existing UPGRADE_NODE_USER environment variable you
can override but this wires that up to the script cli as -U or
--overcloud-user. This is especially useful for split stack
environments where the default overcloud admin user is 'stack'
and not 'heat-admin'.

Closes-Bug: 1724550
Change-Id: Idb8f87119028480df49bd3ee8cc8e6ddd599fc72

commit_message:
[bfv] Set the correct iqn for pxe

Set the initiator iqn to the connecting node not the target.

Closes-Bug: #1724275
Change-Id: Ife5570c2eebeded360ace8d37c699726b2661d44
(cherry picked from commit 217b3f84ac96497d6ea5871a8ea824170368026c)

This PS showcases the usage of fluent-prometheus plugin for metrics

'sum' function has to be used because there may be many fluentd instances.

commit_message:
Log based metrics using fluent-plugin-prometheus.

This PS showcases the usage of fluent-prometheus plugin for metrics
collection based on docker logs. As an example, one metric 'mysql_errors'
is collected and exposed to Prometheus through REST API at
ip:port/metrics path. Fluent uses grepcounter to count occurrences of
"Can't connect to MySQL" log. Then, the number is exposed to Prometheus.

New service (service-prometheus-fluentd.yaml) has been created so that
Prometheus can reach fluend target and gather metrics exposed by fluentd.
Thanks to "prometheus_service_annotations", no additional configuration
in Prometheus is needed to make the target visible for Prometheus.
Service is annotated with additional fields (prometheus.io/*) so
Prometheus can dynamically find this endpoint and treat it as its target.

The following image:
https://pasteboard.co/GQpJ6r4.png
presents 'mysql_errors' metrics graph. For the first couple of minutes,
mariadb endpoint was not reachable what caused the counter to increase
over time. After 8th minute, mariadb was reachable again and the counter
was stable. Please note that in order to make it working correctly,
'sum' function has to be used because there may be many fluentd instances.

New Docker image is needed in order to make use of grepcounter, typecast
and prometheus plugins.

Change-Id: Ie3cff83102980d560065d2b4b32b1bcc953ae65b
Signed-off-by: Mateusz Blaszkowski <mateusz.blaszkowski@intel.com>

commit_message:
Add API tests for Tag resource with standard attribute

This patch added some api tests for tag resource with standard
attribute, which are securitygroup, floatingip, trunk, and policy.

In TagFilter test, identifier of resource was changed from name to
id because floatingip doesn't have name attribute.

Change-Id: I3a20abe00d4cb32b1a84aeb7b05429e776244c3e
Related-bug: #1682775

commit_message:
use external net api def from lib

The external network extension's API definition was rehomed into
neutron-lib with I9933b91d1e82db3891b3b72f06e94316e56a4f15. This patch
consumes it, switching over to neutron-lib's modules in prep for
I696b52265b9528082cd2524f05febe2338376488

commit_message:
Run pep8 everywhere

Since the Zuul v2 files are removed, we can lint pep8 with less changes
everywhere. Enable pep8 linting everywhere and fix remaining problems.

Depends-On: Id67d0149b645bd23e460cef65719541f76f0967b
Change-Id: I0ac0709b05912d00d02a51d732b1cf12eaf888a5

Allow outward_rabbitmq with enable_outward_rabbitmq

outward_rabbitmq is determined  using enable_outward_rabbitmq
property rather than current haproxy_enable_external_vip

Change-Id: Iee096ab50fd4d9f5f3fe05880d0e0a7842c59d0a

commit_message:
placement: integrate ProviderTree to report client

This patch uses the new ProviderTree object as the compute-side cache
of resource provider and inventory information within the scheduler
reporting client. Using the ProviderTree enables the nested resource
provider modeling in later patches.

Change-Id: Ic032e8eb9f99756537848c01af20e1c533a045ee
Co-Authored-By: Jay Pipes <jaypipes@gmail.com>

use external net api def from lib

The external network extension's API definition was rehomed into
neutron-lib with I9933b91d1e82db3891b3b72f06e94316e56a4f15. This patch
consumes it, switching over to neutron-lib's modules in prep for

commit_message:
Remove references to the current task from task() in validations.yaml

When using the task() expression function within a mistral task the name
is only needed when referncing a different task. These were found with
the mistral-lint PyPI package.

Change-Id: Ib3dabfee507d715731157468341c28b0bdd2281d

I think an even better improvement in terms of speed would be to generate the inventory only once in a common location for all the non-controller nodes. So generate the static inventory while running upgrade-non-controller.sh the first time and the subsequent runs of upgrade-non-controller.sh should the already generated inventory. I think that during upgrade we don't expect changes in the deployment which would result in a different invetory so it should be safe. WDYT?"}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2017-10-18 12:02:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

agree with mcornea that we could optimize this a bit, otherwise lgtm for a first pass'}, {'account_id': 8449, 'date': '2017-10-18 13:23:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

ack thanks for the reviews. I think i'll update it one more time then. I am going to just add a --tripleo-ansible-inventory option so that the operator can pass it if they want to re-use the inventory from last run.
We could also use a 'well known' location (like /home/stack/inventory) and then even try to detect if we should generate the inventory or not. Using a known location is prone to error from any left over/previous runs.

Let see what folks think when i update it."}, {'account_id': 20775, 'date': '2017-10-18 13:48:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 18851, 'date': '2017-10-18 14:37:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2017-10-18 14:43:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

Looks good to me - while I can see the potential performance advantages of generating once in a common location, we'll need to ensure it's documented to regenerated it every time the overcloud stack is updated - increasingly it'll contain data/vars and not only the node manifest so we'll have to be careful to avoid drift between the heat generated outputs and the locally cached manifests."}, {'account_id': 8449, 'date': '2017-10-18 14:47:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> Looks good to me - while I can see the potential performance

 > stack is updated - increasingly it'll contain data/vars and not
 > only the node manifest so we'll have to be careful to avoid drift
 > between the heat generated outputs and the locally cached
 > manifests.

ack thanks shardy. there was some discussion about it this afternoon too. I'm tempted to add a --ansible-manifest option so the operator can just override if they want to. But it could also be an optimization and in general my concern is to keep this script as simple as possible (detect logic etc is not gona be nice in bash :/)

So we could merge this and consider optimising it if we have time?"}, {'account_id': 8449, 'date': '2017-10-18 15:19:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Get a static inventory for upgrade-non-controller ansible runs

This is mainly used together with the newly added --overcloud-user
option and allows us to specify a custom overcloud admin user
e.g. in split stack environments 'stack' vs 'heat-admin'. The
static inventory is generated with the specified user.

As a further optimisation this also adds a new --inventory (-I)
option with which a previously generated inventory can be
specified.

This is also expected to be more efficient since we now only
generate the inventory at most once per node/invocation.

Change-Id: If0d5ca461ce6faf84c26a75bf9ab9e72bb061e7a
Closes-Bug: 1724552

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-07-27 18:22:43.000000000', 'message': 'shim ml2 driver_api with neutron-lib's api

neutron-lib contains the ML2 driver_api module and while we'd like to
switch over to lib's version, we have a significant number of consumers
[1]. Therefore this patch proposes to shim to the remaining public
driver_api like we did in I99e3de6d933a1bb341394f85415fb07306a82a01.

A subsequent patch will move neutron's imports over to use lib's version
of the module; this patch is intended to be "self testing" in that it
assures the shim works in neutron (for neutron's gate anyway).

[1] http://codesearch.openstack.org/?q=from%20neutron.plugins.ml2%20import%20driver_api

Change-Id: I86a10091b55d1123e8d16f16155e0312bb10e54c

commit_message:
shim ml2 driver_api with neutron-lib's api

neutron-lib contains the ML2 driver_api module and while we'd like to
switch over to lib's version, we have a significant number of consumers
[1]. Therefore this patch proposes to shim to the remaining public
driver_api like we did in I99e3de6d933a1bb341394f85415fb07306a82a01.

A subsequent patch will move neutron's imports over to use lib's version
of the module; this patch is intended to be "self testing" in that it
assures the shim works in neutron (for neutron's gate anyway).

[1] http://codesearch.openstack.org/?q=from%20neutron.plugins.ml2%20import%20driver_api

Change-Id: I86a10091b55d1123e8d16f16155e0312bb10e54c

The create_volume_type_extra_specs API in volume types_client actually
contains both 'create' and 'update' function for extra specs of a volume
type. The 'update' function not only can update volume type's existed
extra specs, but also can add new extra specs to the volume type. This
patch adds test for this 'update' function.

commit_message:
Fix test case for updating volume type extra specs

The create_volume_type_extra_specs API in volume types_client actually
contains both 'create' and 'update' function for extra specs of a volume
type. The 'update' function not only can update volume type's existing
extra specs, but also can add new extra specs to the volume type. This
patch adds test for this 'update' function.

Change-Id: Iaa7c760920267c7db58650fc120e8c9033e875d7

commit_message:
revise add_member and remove_member functionality in lb_policy

Use context instead of action object since we only need the context
object to do DB query.

Another reason is that we need to revise the detaching process to
remove members from existed lb pool which means we need to use
the utility method.

Change-Id: I70d07d769c3b7c3748c4bcf904b5c65802b96a68

commit_message:
Fix subnets can not be deleted from network topology panel

The structure of DetailView was changed, so the url for the delete
subnet action needs to be updated so that subnets can be deleted properly.

Added the required method get_subnets_data in DetailView.

Added JS code to remove the subnet from the network node on network
topology panel after the subnet is deleted.

Fixed router interface not being removed from the network topology
panel after it's deleted.

Closes-bug: #1643414

Change-Id: I60cc161655b994c8e3ace5efc37459f3e9e60d67
(cherry picked from commit fb4ae6bbda8f45429bf1c5f34a61292586847742)

commit_message:
Fix logo in IE11/Edge browsers

IE11/Edge browsers doesn't scale SVG images correct if
weight and height is specified directly in SVG. Also these
browsers doesn't work well with max-height style.

Change-Id: I3fe643dd5e0d47cb0e5a658c84d23a8750c217e7
Closes-Bug: #1715674
(cherry picked from commit 502cffb1f8d2f476cff682e6aba15f71ee49c3ef)

commit_message:
Always pass docker-ha env when passing docker env

This does not break anything, and passing only the docker env can break
in cases where the docker and docker-ha were previously included.

Change-Id: I21bb7ac0068a20824c212969bc5f2ea2b5d58b77

commit_message:
Implement APIs for mounting Cinder volumes

Add a new attribute 'mounts' to the request to create a container.
Users can use this attribute to specify one or multiple mounts for
the container. Each mount could specify the source and destination.
The source is the Cinder volume id or name, and the destination is
the path where the file or directory will be mounted in the container.
For examples:

  [{'source': 'my-vol', 'destination': '/data'}]

Partial-Implements: blueprint direct-cinder-integration
Change-Id: Ic11c0bba499ce107a7fab35059671c3d4254d343

commit_message:
Remove network_standalone variable

This is a minor refactoring of the driver code. The variable
network_standalone is used for testing if the driver should
provision and setup the network. However, it is possible to
achieve the same without using this variable. This patch proposes
to remove this variable to make the code look better.

Partial-Implements: blueprint direct-cinder-integration
Change-Id: Ic8f298c10bd4ed74e04c8ec5c2974abb64b8391d

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-02-14 10:10:07.000000000', 'message': "Fix referring to wrong cobbler profile in ubuntu release data

Apparently, release metadata contained referring to wrong cobbler
profile. That cobbler profile was used a while ago for native
installer purposes and became invalid since only IBP method of
provisioning remained.

The problem is that every node will be added to cobbler with
wrong profile and enabled netbooting. If provisioning failed for
some reasons, then the node won't boot because of stale broken links
to initrd and kernel.

`generator_arg` should reffer to valid name of cobbler profile for
 bootstrap image.

For 8.0 and newer, it should be 'ubuntu_bootstrap'
For 7.0 it should be 'bootstrap' (which stands for centos bootstrap)

Change-Id: I86c1cc2501281a85878ac584096a7d12dc4576da
Closes-Bug: #1626962

commit_message:
Fix referring to wrong cobbler profile in ubuntu release data

Apparently, release metadata contained referring to wrong cobbler
profile. That cobbler profile was used a while ago for native
installer purposes and became invalid since only IBP method of
provisioning remained.

The problem is that every node will be added to cobbler with
wrong profile and enabled netbooting. If provisioning failed for
some reasons, then the node won't boot because of stale broken links
to initrd and kernel.

`generator_arg` should reffer to valid name of cobbler profile for
 bootstrap image.

For 8.0 and newer, it should be 'ubuntu_bootstrap'
For 7.0 it should be 'bootstrap' (which stands for centos bootstrap)

Change-Id: I86c1cc2501281a85878ac584096a7d12dc4576da
Closes-Bug: #1626962

commit_message:
Add packages tftpd-hpa and syslinux to requirements

fuel-mirror does not download two packages that are required
when installing Ubuntu-based Openstack control nodes: tftpd-hpa
and syslinux.

Change-Id: I061c64dc8d9a910a869ead1839a2f39227dc5159
Related-Bug: #1562087

commit_message:
Add override variables for plugin

Allow a plugin to override the admin and public addresses using
swift_hash:

- swift_hash['management_vip']
- swift_hash['public_vip']

Partially implements: blueprint detach-components-from-controllers

Conflicts:
	deployment/puppet/osnailyfacter/modular/swift/keystone.pp
	tests/noop/astute.yaml/neut_vlan.ironic.controller.yaml

Change-Id: I90f727451081052c14e0bea896f6faab01f15486

commit_message:
All offline nodes are removed as failed nodes

remove_failed_nodes took only newly deployed nodes uids into
consideration for checking for offline nodes. Now all nodes in cluster
are checked for being available.

Change-Id: Ifbdec3d6f8cd1b2751afb45c185efd5c5316a817
Closes-bug: #1502295

commit_message:
Remove Pike-only migration step

In Pike, plans were migrated from using Mistral environments for
storing parameters values to using a plan-environment.yaml file stored
together with the plan in Swift. New plans created from THT have this
file included automatically from Pike, and the migration step is no
longer necessary starting in Queens.

As of now, fast-forward upgrades will involve upgrading the undercloud
from N to N+1 until N+3 is reached so removing the step isn't an issue.

Change-Id: I4227df5c692ab09b88f84ad60bf241c0b8251f80

commit_message:
Nodegroup can be created not only for GRE

Before: Nodegroup creation fails for non-GRE environmets with
an error
"403 Client Error: Forbidden (Node groups can only be created
when using Neutron GRE.)"

After: Nodegroup is created for non-GRE environmets with a
warning:
"WARNING: Node groups should be used for OpenStack environments
 that use an encapsulation protocol such as Neutron GRE."

Closes-Bug: #1472322
Depends-On: Iaa35fe16a02d73ced7a87a0c7ac2d167d1e77740
Change-Id: I56d70e7ca21b47f161dd85108c09ad54186f872e
Signed-off-by: Andrzej Skupien <askupien@mirantis.com>
(cherry picked from commit b4e5f432f09a8dede206e0fece27810ce5a19b65)

commit_message:
Ensure node interface names are unique within node

Add a constraint on interface names that ensures that they are unique
within node. Make it deferrable so that chain renaming is possible
(e.g. (0, eth0) > (0, eth1); (1, eth1) > (1, eth0))

Change-Id: I0cf3ce3b6391ac7208193d47f588cb98d7c5b452

commit_message:
Allow '_' in node interface names

To facilitate assigning arbitrary names to network interfaces,
the underlying code that creates udev rules must be modified.
Fuel agent expects mapping of MAC addresses to interface names to
be in the following format: <mac>_<ifname> and splits the entry
without limiting the number of splits. If <ifname> contains '_'
this code will produce 'ValueError: too many values to unpack' error.
This patch fixes this behaviour by limiting the number of splits to 1.

Change-Id: Ie7043be8b2bfc5025d9563eb97157f73a8eb1296

commit_message:
Add API for renaming network interfaces

This patch adds the following new API endpoints:
    /nodes/interfaces/logical_names
    /nodes/<node_id>/interfaces/logical_names
which allow to query and modify network interface names.

Renaming itself is performed by NetworkManager.rename_interfaces
class method.

Change-Id: I78aac03f4d780b16c975378a55e11dece0c85a96

commit_message:
Add timeout value to 'urlaccesscheck check'

This change adds a configurable timeout to 'urlaccesscheck check' to
ensure the script does not hang if there are connectivity issues with
the URL that is being checked.  The default timeout is 60 seconds but
is configurable via a command line option.

This change also adds netifaces to the network_checker requirements.txt
because it was not added as part of
I910c15c2b39a917eb8428bb69271b5dde364b639 so test and installation may
fail on a clean environment.

Conflicts:
    network_checker/url_access_checker/api.py

Change-Id: I363712a6501cc21b89601d5373b5633d5518ca81
Closes-Bug: 1478138
Related-Bug: 1471085
Related-Bug: 1476831
Closed-Bug: 1478622

commit_message:
Add MySQL configs and log-files to the diagnostic snapshot

This will be added to the diagnostic snapshot:
 - /etc/mysql/*
 - /var/log/mysql/*
 - commands/mysql_resources.txt
The file commands/mysql_resources.txt will contain the listing files
from the /var/lib/mysql/ and /var/run/mysqld/ directories.

Change-Id: Iddaa9e0d51a02e0d2962dc797c4c1d1cd35b949e
Closes-Bug: #1550984
(cherry picked from commit 9d810891ffc5d93820de6756b1089546ee78bf73)

commit_message:
Change apache2 CGI module for RadosGW

In apache-2.4.7 fastcgi module is not support chunked transfer.
It breaks uploads of objects to RadosGW.
Fix available since apache-2.4.10 (vivid) and upgrade apache in MOS is not
possible, so this workaround proposed.
RadosGW runs with native CGI server on 127.0.0.1:9000 and apache uses
mod_proxy_fcgi to proxy user requests to rados.

Closes-bug: #1505273

Conflicts:
    deployment/puppet/ceph/manifests/init.pp
	deployment/puppet/ceph/templates/rgw.conf.erb
	tests/noop/spec/hosts/ceph/radosgw_spec.rb

Change-Id: Ia3959c4009c6c673074a9b7536b1cc87834c301d
(cherry picked from commit b092234605defaf6e41b15dc949472bd4b2d04ee)

commit_message:
Fix clickjacking attack vulnerability in nginx

For Fuel web interface and other sites served by nginx on fuel master
we should use X-Frame-Options SAMEORIGIN to prevent from clickjacking,
e.g. the page can only be displayed in a frame on the same
origin as the page itself.

Cherry-pick from: f3bbdb9f48bbbe105fce430ed457fb353a95db9a
Closes-Bug: #1497194
Change-Id: Ie8d6e4e92222ac9bb7c489dd0a5aff833fabe873

commit_message:
mysql logs should output to /var/log/mysql

All mysql logs should be in /var/log/mysql so they are properly
captured by shotgun for diagnostic reports.

Change-Id: Id3812a25a235bc64db530d693112c51eaca0579f
Closes-Bug: #1550984
(cherry picked from commit 5446d2e0aaa441d808a328c3ffd37ad0e390a5a6)

"}, {'created': '2016-05-19 12:27:00.000000000', 'message': "Port RabbitMQ OCF script from 9.0 to 6.x

This commit picks the current state of 9.0 into 6.1 Below are listed
added commits. Several commits were ported not fully because of
their unimportance. Such commits are marked in the list. Most of them
are non-functional as a result and are needed only to simplify the
porting of other commits on top of them.

* Fix chowning for rabbit OCF
  (b5ae83a15be191d46d4b0da3d4bc67420311896a)

* Fix error return codes for rabbit OCF
  (5097d94f5d56fd6126ca9b7c1227961536c94399)

* Implement the dumping of rabbitMQ definitions
  The commit has only RabbitMQ OCF part ported. The commit has
  no effect as a result.
  (8ccdfc62152de8212ba6a0aeed45c1e3677c70a4)

* Fix rabbitmq data restore for large datasets
  (11c4e4c3985949f776367dd5045102c6398aef89)

* Add more logs to rabbitmq get_status function
  (60d5743c41999a43d87374357866cd3c3c02aa64)

* Return NOT_RUNNING when beam is not RUNNING
  (00f28b5cc48bdba389922fa460e4a6e6e173589e)

* Wait for rabbitmq sync before stop/demote actions
  (9ca5b6709cd18c8134cd8feaccf937ef49a625b4)

* Sync rabbitmq OCF from upstream
  (fe4edc4589ff37647134fdf83fc4e8896469cdd7)

* Fix the timeout arg for the su_rabbit_cmd
  (0204868a14ac0aa310fc135135a88b6aec576d8c)

* Fix piped exit codes expectations and count processing
  (cf02b81f21845087a328350cb95b8d1e90902cc0)

* Bind rabbitmq, epmd, and management plugin to internal IP
  The commit has only RabbitMQ OCF part ported. Since another part
  is not ported, the commit has no effect.
  (b47944a393e1720b8646abee45bd9c0af56a7b19)

* Add ability to disable HA for RabbitMQ queues
  (7e96ef47caeae03cf9696a67817e1756e1b63f4a)

* Fix default value for 'use_fqdn' in meta_data
  (4a87ef9f2a1977813869ff42ab01ef89f36d92dc)

* Fix monitor/stop operations for the rabbit OCF resource
  (247d4b2612d97dafa557948fb7c7caa755007b2a)

* Ensure rabbit node uptime is reset in the CIB for OCF resource
  (51b4072521684a19c2ba7d394cf8d42b191ced93)

* Fix rabbitMQ OCF monitor detection of running master
  (88fbc08e75a1f1d1e59047f18dfbd5e7b35b9c17)

* Introduce node name prefix for mgmt/messaging IPs
  The commit has only RabbitMQ OCF part ported. Since another part
  is not ported, the commit has no effect.
  (5724477c83cb0aad179484a8f60eca9e026f9715)

* Reset master score if we decide to restart RabbitMQ on timeout
  (5f31ad4a21dd31a268120c866eca252b3683e38a)

* Improve OCF script diagnostics for timed-out 'list_channels'
  (98a0698b7e177dee08f972a48fedc817cc9167a7)

* Fix uninitialized variable in rabbitmq script
  (a464778071a8ccb459bd7b01cdc0e47fadb1f651)

* Fix uninitialized status_master
  (b0f86ec4e8580b17af550defc335e9f6ba8bd5f5)

* Fix action_stop for the rabbit OCF
  (d3b77ffa1581145015726255c956d937c2b273e2)

* Do not check cluster health if master is not elected
  (3dac123119ee5456db177f71631f14d6fc217776)

* Exit waiting loop once node has unjoined
  (5a0c334b73db1e708e418179ff7d1629c30241f0)

* On neighbor promotion do nothing if we are already clustered
  (8d81f4a26961b6c55bb5e0f4d8f942be0fd92669)

* Increase tolerable number of rabbitmqctl timeouts
  (9fc444092a6e809ee90116845c07c7cfebda46ce)

* Suppress curl progress indicator in rabbit OCF
  (ec3961fce644ad915209609d360bc979b184a94e)

* Log process id in RabbitMQ OCF script
  (01b1506830e141a06b744c81cdb3c7ed68535b26)

* Put the RabbitMQ OCF RA policy to /usr/sbin
  (8ebd9b12998358bd3a0d8dd2040d18875689fb54)

* Stop a rabbitmq pacemaker resource when monitor fails
  (b684391018bb3d8cac20083d9217ba821cf02384)

* Stop process when rabbit is running but is not connected to master.
  (43886f7b51c4e67d5006f099c1b35efd2dc71685)

* Fix half-hearted attempt to erase mnesia in OCF RA
  (a2d9314432c5d7c31c18ffb981e9cf2c20898607)

Partial-Bug: #1581706
Change-Id: I4c51f8608702f2284d835ba9c3c9070b2c329ed8

commit_message:
Port RabbitMQ OCF script from 9.0 to 6.x

This commit picks the current state of 9.0 into 6.1 Below are listed
added commits. Several commits were ported not fully because of
their unimportance. Such commits are marked in the list. Most of them
are non-functional as a result and are needed only to simplify the
porting of other commits on top of them.

* Fix chowning for rabbit OCF
  (b5ae83a15be191d46d4b0da3d4bc67420311896a)

* Fix error return codes for rabbit OCF
  (5097d94f5d56fd6126ca9b7c1227961536c94399)

* Implement the dumping of rabbitMQ definitions
  The commit has only RabbitMQ OCF part ported. The commit has
  no effect as a result.
  (8ccdfc62152de8212ba6a0aeed45c1e3677c70a4)

* Fix rabbitmq data restore for large datasets
  (11c4e4c3985949f776367dd5045102c6398aef89)

  (60d5743c41999a43d87374357866cd3c3c02aa64)

  (7e96ef47caeae03cf9696a67817e1756e1b63f4a)

  (4a87ef9f2a1977813869ff42ab01ef89f36d92dc)

  (247d4b2612d97dafa557948fb7c7caa755007b2a)

* Ensure rabbit node uptime is reset in the CIB for OCF resource
  (51b4072521684a19c2ba7d394cf8d42b191ced93)

* Fix rabbitMQ OCF monitor detection of running master
  (88fbc08e75a1f1d1e59047f18dfbd5e7b35b9c17)

* Introduce node name prefix for mgmt/messaging IPs
  The commit has only RabbitMQ OCF part ported. Since another part
  is not ported, the commit has no effect.
  (5724477c83cb0aad179484a8f60eca9e026f9715)

* Reset master score if we decide to restart RabbitMQ on timeout

* Fix uninitialized variable in rabbitmq script
  (a464778071a8ccb459bd7b01cdc0e47fadb1f651)

* Fix uninitialized status_master

* Fix action_stop for the rabbit OCF

* Do not check cluster health if master is not elected

* Exit waiting loop once node has unjoined

* On neighbor promotion do nothing if we are already clustered

commit_message:
Fix the problem with ceph deployment on scale lab

Postpone ceph pool creation to post deploy:
* Add task for ceph pool creation and put it in post deploy
* Change ceph/compute.pp and move to post deploy
* Remove from ceph/manifests/init.pp the pool creation code

Change-Id: I05b53042e24da8cb1693049bd95e682c8903c812
Closes-bug: #1462451

commit_message:
Add apache mod_proxy for ceph radosgw

With the switch to fcgi for radosgw we need to include mod_proxy as
mod_proxy_fcgi requires it. This change pulls in the proxy module to
resolve apache2 startup failures when ceph is enabled.

Closes-Bug: #1505273
(cherry picked from commit ac654f2a5bac67ee8bd8330cb4b8443a84b3ea28)

Change-Id: I7044b58066e70b11ed9358579a2f369ce761ee06

commit_message:
All offline nodes are removed as failed nodes

remove_failed_nodes took only newly deployed nodes uids into
consideration for checking for offline nodes. Now all nodes in cluster
are checked for being available.

Change-Id: Ifbdec3d6f8cd1b2751afb45c185efd5c5316a817
Closes-bug: #1502295

commit_message:
Add tox.ini with pep8 tests to fix CI

* Add tox.ini with pep8 tests so 'gate-fuel-web-pep8' is able to
  actually run
* Ignore all existing pep8 errors and warnings to unblock merging in
  stable/6.0, but prevent any more pep8 errors and warnings

Change-Id: Iad59da7f8e5af901e7c9fa830f3a6ebe81d021b3
Related-Bug: #1511787

commit_message:
Remove ntpd -gqd from sync admin node test

As long as we check time by ntpdate when master node syncs in 'try' block,
we don't have to do it again in 'else' block, cause it worthless. So, we
can easily remove it from there.

Change-Id: I6c8ead50b9f0f1f423da0162294d4ba7bdfbb3ed
Closes-Bug: #1420815

commit_message:
Implement setting availability zone hint on network creation

If the 'network_availability_zone'-extension is enabled, this patch adds a
field to the Create Network-workflow named 'Availability Zone Hints'.

Change-Id: Ic4206d5765c2d01afedf0e64f9aa50ffce76b661

commit_message:
Add tox.ini with pep8 tests to fix CI

* Add tox.ini with pep8 tests so 'gate-fuel-web-pep8' is able to
  actually run
* Ignore all existing pep8 errors and warnings to unblock merging in
  stable/5.1, but prevent any more pep8 errors and warnings

Change-Id: Iad59da7f8e5af901e7c9fa830f3a6ebe81d021b3
Related-Bug: #1511787

commit_message:
Backport logrotate changes from 6.1

* use tabooext to ensure no overlap between Fuel's cron job and the
  system one
* run logrotate twice an hour
* merge weekly and daily configuration files
* rotate logs basing on two criteria: age and size
* use dateformat to make rotated logs' filename more readable
* enable delayed compression to avoid race condition between
  fuel-logrotate and regular logrotate
* combine CentOS and Ubuntu logrotate wrappers to a single file

Related-Bug: 1382515
Related-Bug: 1450039
Related-Bug: 1461400
Closes-Bug:  1472179
Change-Id: I58caf3c93943af818a03e07d534ff8c42a63d2cb
