commit_message:
Introduce Cinder volume driver

* Define the volume driver interface that all volume drivers
  need to inherit. Currently, the interface has three methods:
  attach, detach, and bind_mount. Attach should connect to
  the volume and mount the volume to a specific path in the
  filesystem for containers to bindmount. Detach should do
  the opposite of attach. Bind_mount returns the host and
  container paths that the binding should use.
* Implement the first volume driver for Cinder. This driver
  is for mounting/unmounting Cinder volumes. It uses the
  CinderWorkflow API to attach/detach Cinder volumes and
  using the mounting utility to mount the attached volumes
  to the filsystem.

Partial-Implements: blueprint direct-cinder-integration
Change-Id: I602bdf7127f298a2193d3143b05188ec8ebfb64e

commit_message:
Fix post gate hook to accommodate for new os-testr

New os-testr uses stestr under the hood, which creates
.stestr but not .testrepository directory in the current dir.
Other than that, it doesn't seem like there is any difference
in the format or names of files generated in the directory.

Change-Id: I81987263b7df293bf53564d6e97726a4fc9d4e90
Closes-Bug: 1716746

commit_message:
Add the api works num for watcher

Number of workers for Watcher api service can not be configure, this
patch to fix it.

refer to https://github.com/openstack/watcher/blob/master/watcher/conf/api.py#L43

Change-Id: I2763b8e225ceb4b8e067d53b8d5f0ffba31563a6

commit_message:
Handle ldap size limit exeeded exception

LDAP servers have sizelimit configuration to limit the number of
user/group objects that can be returned for an LDAP query. This
change catches the size limit exceeded exception when users/groups
returned from ldap search query exceeds the configured limit and
responds with an appropriate error message instead of default
500 error message.

Change-Id: I9949bb7d458b4b037616c701e0e4d362bfa36473
Closes-Bug: #1712415

gives the container direct access to the host processes, so someone can bypass to the host (ie: libvirt process). Pid_host should only be used when is strictly necessary'}, {'account_id': 26999, 'date': '2017-10-10 09:47:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Yes, there are potential harms indeed as you say, but skydive doesnot support recognize nested namespace now'}, {'account_id': 8994, 'date': '2017-10-10 10:10:12.000000000', 'content': 'Removed Code-Review-1 by Sylvain Baubeau <sbaubeau@redhat.com>
'}, {'account_id': 26999, 'date': '2017-10-11 01:46:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Another way, add option in globals.yml rather set pid=host by default, Do you guys agree???'}, {'account_id': 23717, 'date': '2017-10-11 03:50:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

> gives the container direct access to the host processes, so someone
 > can bypass to the host (ie: libvirt process). Pid_host should only
 > be used when is strictly necessary

agree'}, {'account_id': 26999, 'date': '2017-10-15 05:15:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Eduardo Gonzalez, neutron-{dhcp,l3}-agent and skydive-agent must be in pid=host simultaneously, otherwise skydive cannot work . Or do you have a better idea?'}, {'account_id': 2888, 'date': '2017-10-17 10:04:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

this bug should already be fixed by I41cc1fd0fdeae0757a2c4e3e310ec6375da0b8cf'}, {'account_id': 26999, 'date': '2017-10-17 10:19:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Mathieu Rohon,  ns created in host can be recognized, but ns created in dhcp/l3 agent container cannot be recognized'}, {'account_id': 19316, 'date': '2017-10-17 10:27:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Access to host namespaces is access to containers with namespaces on it.

l3 and dhcp namespaces reside in hosts, there is no need to connect to containers'}, {'account_id': 26999, 'date': '2017-10-17 11:04:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

dhcp/l3 container reside on non-root pid namespace, thus ns created by dhcp/l3 container has difference with ns created in root pid namespace'}, {'account_id': 19316, 'date': '2017-10-17 11:09:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

what does it means, qrouter/qdhcp/fips reside in host's namespaces"}, {'account_id': 26999, 'date': '2017-10-17 11:31:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

it has different value for "DEVICE" field by command "stat /var/run/netns/$NSMAME" in different pid namespace, and skydive just work base on the "DEVICE" value.'}, {'account_id': 2888, 'date': '2017-10-17 12:21:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I must be missing something, since to me, netns created by the l3-agent are not in the l3-agent container, but directly on the host running the l3-agent container.

In my config, I can see qrouter, qdhcp namespaces.'}, {'account_id': 8994, 'date': '2017-10-17 14:05:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@jinke I'm working on a patch on the Skydive side that may fix the problem. Do you mind giving it a try once it's ready ?"}, {'account_id': 26999, 'date': '2017-10-17 14:34:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Mathieu Rohon, 
when dhcp/l3 agent container in pid namespace,skydive just treat ns as  tap port seen in webui of skydive, But when dhcp/l3 agent container in pid=host mode, skydive can recognize ns within there are loopback and tap port.
The key problem lies in webui of skydive.

@Sylvain Baubeau, Yes, when patch ready, I would like to try'}, {'account_id': 19316, 'date': '2017-10-17 14:42:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

btw, in case this patch is still usefull after the skydive fix, is missing a check in config.yml in neutron and skydive roles for pid_mode or wont be applied in reconfigure/upgrade'}, {'account_id': 26999, 'date': '2017-10-18 06:03:39.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 26999, 'date': '2017-10-23 10:36:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I'd like you to reexamine a change.  Please visit
to look at the new patch set ."}, {'account_id': 8994, 'date': '2017-10-24 14:44:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@jinke We just pushed this patch https://github.com/skydive-project/skydive/commit/2e6aed2354b1487a8b236c42667333e242907bd7

Could you please give it a try ?

(If you want to avoid the compilation of Skydive, we provide binaries for the master branch here https://github.com/skydive-project/skydive-binaries)'}, {'account_id': 26999, 'date': '2017-10-25 01:56:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Sylvain Baubeau, I have verified with skydive-latest provided by you, and it work well, this change will be abandon, Thanks'}, {'account_id': 26999, 'date': '2017-10-25 01:56:36.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

resolved by skydive side'}]

commit_message:
Conditionalize syslinux requirement

A non-bios architecture will not have a syslinux package and
therefore cannot assume that it must be installed.

Change-Id: I02e2cb556efe94c68f63e1b919b66cc1a5b9e5b1

commit_message:
Remove the use of deprecated attributes in novaclient calls.

The trove log files flagged these Novaclient attributes as deprecated:
  - bypass_url
  - tenant_id
  - management_url

This patch replaced them with updated attributes.

Closes-bug: 1712869
Change-Id: I7b560176315513b96f3d3eea5a0023fb071cbaff

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more

commit_message:
Fix for neutron database field name

A field in the database changed from tenant_id to project_id,
this is a fix to correct that in astara.

Change-Id: I06da92561187e7e4682005e1e15339d1d7ab1e08
Closes-bug: 1642057

For better cross-SQL database support we need to actually
use a boolean datatype for Boolean() fields rather than expecting
implict type conversion.

Without this change, sql operations are failing with traces
similar to

ERROR oslo_db.sqlalchemy.exc_filters [-] DBAPIError exception wrapped from (psycopg2.ProgrammingError) operator does not exist: boolean = integer

Change-Id: Ic444197b5406a9c87d41f3a034ca9eeaa0e43523
'}]
commit_message:
Stricter use of Boolean type in database queries

For better cross-SQL database support we need to actually
use a boolean datatype for Boolean() fields rather than expecting
implict type conversion.

Without this change, sql operations are failing with traces
similar to

ERROR oslo_db.sqlalchemy.exc_filters [-] DBAPIError exception wrapped from (psycopg2.ProgrammingError) operator does not exist: boolean = integer

Change-Id: Ic444197b5406a9c87d41f3a034ca9eeaa0e43523

[{'created': '2017-10-10 18:06:11.000000000', 'message': "Preserve X-Static-Large-Object from .data file after POST

You can't modify the X-Static-Large-Object metadata with a POST, an
object being a SLO is a property of the .data file.  Revert the change
from 4500ff which attempts to correctly handle X-Static-Large-Object
metadata on a POST, but is subject to a race if the most recent SLO
.data isn't available during the POST.  Instead this change adjusts the
reading of metadata such that the X-Static-Large-Object metadata is
always preserved from the metadata on the datafile and bleeds through
a .meta if any.

Closes-bug: #1453807
Closes-bug: #1634723

Co-Authored-By: Kota Tsuyuzaki <tsuyuzaki.kota@lab.ntt.co.jp>
Change-Id: Ie48a38442559229a2993443ab0a04dc84717ca59
(cherry picked from commit 36a843be73e2d58c3fe49a049d514b421124bd06)
"}]
commit_message:
Preserve X-Static-Large-Object from .data file after POST

You can't modify the X-Static-Large-Object metadata with a POST, an
object being a SLO is a property of the .data file.  Revert the change
from 4500ff which attempts to correctly handle X-Static-Large-Object
metadata on a POST, but is subject to a race if the most recent SLO
.data isn't available during the POST.  Instead this change adjusts the
reading of metadata such that the X-Static-Large-Object metadata is
always preserved from the metadata on the datafile and bleeds through
a .meta if any.

Closes-bug: #1453807
Closes-bug: #1634723

Co-Authored-By: Kota Tsuyuzaki <tsuyuzaki.kota@lab.ntt.co.jp>
Change-Id: Ie48a38442559229a2993443ab0a04dc84717ca59
(cherry picked from commit 36a843be73e2d58c3fe49a049d514b421124bd06)

commit_message:
shim FAULT_MAP from neutron-lib

Idfd956fa213e1ba6c3b1c983f246c5b515951e6d rehomed the FAULT_MAP into
neutron-lib. Since consumers expect to access the latest faults in this
map which are updated by neutron at runtime, we can't just move
consumers over to lib's version (it won't be updated by neutron).

Therefore this patch shims neutron's FAULT_MAP to use lib's. Once
this shim lands consumers can move to lib's FAULT_MAP (neutron will
ref it via shim) and finally we can then consume in neutron and remove
in a subsequent patch.

The shim herein shouldn't impact consumers so should be free to land
without worry of their impact.

Change-Id: I8e79f29206ec244d870e19f99c18ccaaa50b4761

commit_message:
Octavia driver to honor Octavia API status codes

Currently the Octavia driver for neutron-lbaas is not honoring Octavia API
status codes. This can lead to a race condition where the status update
thread is behind the actual object status in Octavia.
This updates the driver to raise the appropriate status code to the
neutron API.

Story: 2001257
Task: 5787
(cherry picked from commit cfea70bdc4b759e31ef6a87cdaf79b9d1baea572)

Change-Id: Iad1f8284d22f68c70baff373f9df1c26e207cc71

commit_message:
Don't install iptables rules if neutron is filtering

Don't setup iptables rules in the Linux Bridge driver
if Neutron is providing security groups filtering.
When neutron is providing filtering, it handles everything
ranging from security-group enforcement to anti-spoofing
rules so Nova/os-vif shouldn't need to do anything on plug.

Conflicts:
	vif_plug_linux_bridge/tests/test_plugin.py

Closes-Bug: #1694769

Change-Id: I19d62a8ac730aba2586b9f8eb08e153746ec2bcb
(cherry picked from commit 10e6b6bd1b2b71bf18341719428d68a3f30cb2e9)

commit_message:
Bug Fix For DPDK on Stable/Newton

For vif_type "vhostuser" mechanism driver does not post "vhost_socket_path" to nova
due to which VM creation fails.
Comment Addressed (pep8 error: line too long)

Change-Id: Ifb808c1c2fbafc047371b15d47a4ff00f190c078
Closes-Bug: #1684219
Signed-off-by: Arslan Qadeer <arslanq@xgrid.co>

commit_message:
Enabling support for DHCP Service on OpenDaylight Controller

This is an enhancement to the existing ODL ML2 Driver, wherein it will
create Neutron Ports that are of 'dhcp' device_owner, and such ports
would be used by OpenDaylight Controller to provide DHCP Service. The
Neutron Ports created for each subnet here are for specific use only by
the OpenDaylight Controller DHCP service.  Running stock DHCP Service of
Openstack will continue to be supported with OpenDaylight deployments,
but neutron dhcp ports used by that stock DHCP Service are different and
will continue to be owned and used by the stock DHCP service.

Implements: neutron-port-dhcp
Change-Id: Id12c86b0a7d5b42395058c7c37bf91bc8205016a
Signed-off-by: Achuth Maniyedath <achuth.m@altencalsoftlabs.com>

commit_message:
Add new resource for port bindings

As a result of implementing providing Nova port binding information for
live migration [1], a new resource for callbacks is required. This
resource will be used by the multiple port binding service plugin [2]
to notify the core plugin and other subscribers when create, update and
delete operations are performed on a port binding.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/460021
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/414251

Related-Bug: #1580880

Change-Id: Ibbc7af67cf1282cbf7d9d3a681b9a04a7922c24a

commit_message:
Fix important:: directive display in install guide

The highlighted note about the `default_share_type` config option was
being displayed as part of the code snippet above it due to a misaligned
important:: directive. This patch corrects the spacing so that the note
will display correctly.

TrivialFix

Change-Id: I0b86e86aebc9370e0f84ad669c368c0a2a5eccdd
(cherry picked from commit 54223ca38b051455178ea70788e9c16594aca16b)
(cherry picked from commit 8d52d0dd8b943a950660493486077e1a90eccf0b)

[{'created': '2017-10-24 19:57:39.000000000', 'message': 'Remove "no auth token" debug log

When things go badly and we turn on debug logs, we start seeing this
message about a missing auth token for every auth request. To the
untrained eye, it looks like the culprit when you are debugging auth
problems. In reality, it usually just means the initial POST
/auth/tokens request was sent, which does not include the X-Auth-Token
header. This log adds more confusion than clarify, so this patch removes
itin favor of a code comment.

Change-Id: I4657523a170607d664b73ac1f1ab44d7f1460b33
Closes-bug: #1726736
'}]
commit_message:
Remove "no auth token" debug log

When things go badly and we turn on debug logs, we start seeing this
message about a missing auth token for every auth request. To the
untrained eye, it looks like the culprit when you are debugging auth
problems. In reality, it usually just means the initial POST
/auth/tokens request was sent, which does not include the X-Auth-Token
header. This log adds more confusion than clarify, so this patch removes
itin favor of a code comment.

Change-Id: I4657523a170607d664b73ac1f1ab44d7f1460b33
Closes-bug: #1726736

Update AIO docs for nova examples and Docker image

Update Kubernetes AIO install guide fixing nova
install examples. Also add language around
pulling the AIO container versus building.

The DefaultStandarize object in pypowervm defaults the max virtio
slots number, and nova-powervm always creates the object with the

number to be this default. Currently it is not supported to change

change makes it so that in the resize scenario the max virtio slots
number will remain the same.

commit_message:
Persist existing LPAR wrapper attributes in DefaultStandardize on resize

The DefaultStandardize object in pypowervm defaults the proc units
factor, max virtio slots, uncapped weight, spp, availability
priority, srr, proc compat, and lpar metric values. nova-powervm
does not pass in these parameters when resizing.

This results in these attributes being set to the default defined
by the DefaultStandardize object for every resize operation. This
change passes those parameters into the DefaultStandardize object.

Note that if the attributes were passed in as part of the flavor
then the flavor's values would be set later in the DefaultStandardize
object by the LPARBuilder.

Closes-Bug: #1722923
Change-Id: I0e9ad0dbbc35658e096636a454ad493492025420

Fix domain scope auth in use with endpoint filter

Add check if project_id exists, only than append endpoint list.

commit_message:
Change DevStack plugin to setup multi-Keystone

Change DevStack plugin to allow setup of 2 Keystone services on different
nodes in order to run multinode Grenade job. This plugin will setup HAProxy
in round-robin mode to bind Keystone services together.

Partially-Implements: bp rolling-upgrade-testing

Depends-On: I577eb46b82bef54f89eed5c8a43a472341ff17a6

Change-Id: Idee6a70232b3e7ea65c2c6f67a7b5db352f1614a

commit_message:
Cascade delete federated_user fk

The bug was caused by a foreign key in the federated_user table. This
key prevents a protocol from being deleted after a successful
authentication has happened (so the creation of a federated user
via shadowing). We take advantage of the same foreign key by adding the
cascade delete behavior to it.

Closes-Bug: 1642692

Change-Id: I3b3e265d20f0cfe0ee10c6a274d9bdf4e840b742

commit_message:
Handle disk write failure when doing Fernet key rotation

_create_new_key() is broke down into 2 parts:

1. _create_tmp_new_key()
2. _become_valid_new_key()

This can avoid empty Fernet keys when the write to the
staged key fails. The _become_valid_new_key() is called
only after a successful call to _create_tmp_new_key().

Change-Id: Iaf33e2b291f13b9eb9464ef345a8664a634121ff
Closes-Bug: #1642457
Signed-off-by: John Lin <johnlinp@gmail.com>
(cherry picked from commit 5b7c9a66f0aed860ea0776d4c5b42710d88fcb5f)

commit_message:
Delete users before deleting domains

In the migration process [1], we added a FK for user.domain_id
to domain.id. Users would only be deleted after the domain
delete, when the notification was propagated, however this
would make the FK to break.

This patch fixes the behavior by deleting domain users
before deleting the domain itself.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/keystone/blob/2bd88d3/keystone/common/sql/expand_repo/versions/014_expand_add_domain_id_to_user_table.py#L140-L141

Closes-Bug: #1718747

Change-Id: Iba615826356bd4efcf9fb83c7b239ce9a856102d

commit_message:
Don't update cinder quotas if disabled

The quotas for cinder were being updated even if they were disabled,
resulting in None being sent as the value, and an error being thrown
by the API.

This patch cleans up that code to use the same logic in all three cases
for nova, cinder and neutron.

Change-Id: I73209122df20689eee33da9dccffa994a04a3ec0
Closes-bug: #1671911
(cherry picked from commit 3055a987632c29175c06d73e77fbad9062fcc2c4)

commit_message:
Allow to scale when group is in CHECK_COMPLETE

When a signal of scaling policy arrive, we will find
the group in stack by stack.resource_by_refid(), now
we kick out the group if the it is in CHECK_COMPLETE.
This change will correct this.

commit_message:
Use storage_url in DB for multi-tenant swift store

When using swift multi-tenant store, using a user's service
catalog to obtain the storage url for an object does not work
if the image was not created by the same user. This is because
the user's context, if used to establish a connection, would only
be looking at a location url formed with the wrong owner information
resulting in an object GET failure (404).

This patch solves this issue by a 'revert in principle' to the old code
logic where the storage_url for an image when using multi-tenant store
was fetched from the database via 'location.swift_url'. The change
that had introduced the fetch of storage_url from user's context is [1].

[1] I7bc23dfc11900b55f45fe98144d14f883c381c9f

Co-Authored-By: Hemanth Makkapati <hemanth.makkapati@rackspace.com>
Co-Authored-By: Dharini Chandrasekar <dharini.chandrasekar@intel.com>

Partial-Bug: #1625075

Change-Id: I8c22a0ab566cf1ec99cbee78ea43ef28abcd8dc0
cherry-picked from commit 2b4f75a628bc755cb2f804cadf5e381b01390766

[{'created': '2016-12-08 16:32:13.000000000', 'message': 'Restrict location updates to active, queued images

Currently image location updates (removing, replacing) are permitted for
images even if their state is not ``active``.

This need is to:
 * Prevent the replacement of image locations of images that are not
   ``active`` or ``queued`` by returning a Conflict Error
    (409 response code).
 * Prevent removal of image locations of images that are not ``active``
   by returning a Conflict Error (409 response code).

Changing of image locations when the image state is not ``active`` can
result in bad experiences for the users.
 *  If one tries to change or remove the location for an image while it
    is in ``saving`` state, Glance would be trying to write data to a
    previously saved location while the user updates the custom
    location. This results in a race condition.
 *  For images that are in ``queued`` state and no image data has been
    uploaded yet, there is no need for an image location to be
    removed and permitting users to remove the image
    location can result in a bad experience. However users can be
    allowed to replace the image location to maintain backward
    compatibility and also because replacing could mean replacing an
    empty location by a non-empty image location.
*   For images in ``deactivated`` state, it is essential that image
    locations are not updated as it does not abide with the purpose of
    the image state being set to ``deactivated`` and may cause security
    concerns.

This commit introduces the following change in behavior:
  * If an image is in ``active`` state, removing/replacing the custom
    locations on that image will be allowed so there is no change in
    behavior for this case.
  * If an image is in ``saving`` or ``deactivated``, the status of
    that image will be checked while trying to replace/remove the custom
    location and a HTTP 409 Conflict status will be returned in response
    to the user.
  * If an image is in ``queued`` state, removing the custom
    image location will not be permitted as an image in queued status
    should not have any location associated with it. Replacing of location
    may be permitted here though.
  * If an image is in ``deleted`` or ``pending_delete`` state, a HTTP
    409 Conflict status will be returned, if that image is visible to
    the user (in case of admins). Otherwise, the location cannot be
    removed/replaced anyway.  Please note ``pending_delete`` is another
    form of the ``deleted`` status and behavior in either case should be
    expected to be same.
  * If an image is in ``killed`` status, a HTTP 409 Conflict status will
    be returned.

TODO:
Atomicity is required such that glance permits removal/replacement of
image locations on certain permissible image transition states handling
the race conditions like:
  * In case where the status of the image is ``saving`` and it
    has just moved to ```active`` status, ideally removing/replacing
    custom location should be allowed. However, due to lack of
    atomicity in setting image status glance will ignore setting the
    location and a 409 will be returned.
  * In case where the status of the image is ``deactivated`` and it
    has just been moved to ``active`` status, ideally
    removing/replacing custom location should be allowed. Again, due
    to lack of atomicity in setting image status glance will ignore
    the request and a 409 will be returned.
  * In case where the status of the image is ``active`` and it has
    just been moved to ``deactivated`` status, due to lack of
    atomicity in setting image status, glance may remove/replace
    the location on that image.
  * In case where the status of the image is ``queued`` and it has
    just been moved to ``saving`` status, due to lack of atomicity
    in setting image status, glance may replace the location for
    that image.
  * In case where the status of the image is ``active`` and location
    is attempted to be set on it, and at that point if the image goes
    into ``deleted``, ``pending_delete`` or ``killed`` status, then the
    user must get a HTTP 409 Conflict status. However due to lack of
    atomicity in setting the image status, the location may get updated.

NOTE:
This commit ensures that removal of image locations
is not allowed for an image in any state except ``active`` and
replacement of an image location is not allowed except for ``active``
and ``queued`` images.
Further work is required on the atomicity of glance to accommodate
location updates in cases where the images would be undergoing state
changes.

DocImpact

commit_message:
Restrict location updates to active, queued images

Currently image location updates (removing, replacing) are permitted for
images even if their state is not ``active``.

This need is to:
 * Prevent the replacement of image locations of images that are not
   ``active`` or ``queued`` by returning a Conflict Error
    (409 response code).
 * Prevent removal of image locations of images that are not ``active``
   by returning a Conflict Error (409 response code).

Changing of image locations when the image state is not ``active`` can
result in bad experiences for the users.
 *  If one tries to change or remove the location for an image while it
    is in ``saving`` state, Glance would be trying to write data to a
    previously saved location while the user updates the custom
    location. This results in a race condition.
 *  For images that are in ``queued`` state and no image data has been
    uploaded yet, there is no need for an image location to be
    removed and permitting users to remove the image
    location can result in a bad experience. However users can be
    allowed to replace the image location to maintain backward
    compatibility and also because replacing could mean replacing an
    empty location by a non-empty image location.
*   For images in ``deactivated`` state, it is essential that image
    locations are not updated as it does not abide with the purpose of
    the image state being set to ``deactivated`` and may cause security
    concerns.

This commit introduces the following change in behavior:
  * If an image is in ``active`` state, removing/replacing the custom
    locations on that image will be allowed so there is no change in
    behavior for this case.
  * If an image is in ``saving`` or ``deactivated``, the status of
    that image will be checked while trying to replace/remove the custom
    location and a HTTP 409 Conflict status will be returned in response
    to the user.
  * If an image is in ``queued`` state, removing the custom
    image location will not be permitted as an image in queued status
    should not have any location associated with it. Replacing of location
    may be permitted here though.
  * If an image is in ``deleted`` or ``pending_delete`` state, a HTTP
    409 Conflict status will be returned, if that image is visible to
    the user (in case of admins). Otherwise, the location cannot be
    removed/replaced anyway.  Please note ``pending_delete`` is another
    form of the ``deleted`` status and behavior in either case should be
    expected to be same.
  * If an image is in ``killed`` status, a HTTP 409 Conflict status will
    be returned.

TODO:
Atomicity is required such that glance permits removal/replacement of
image locations on certain permissible image transition states handling
the race conditions like:
  * In case where the status of the image is ``saving`` and it
    has just moved to ```active`` status, ideally removing/replacing
    custom location should be allowed. However, due to lack of
    atomicity in setting image status glance will ignore setting the
    location and a 409 will be returned.
  * In case where the status of the image is ``deactivated`` and it
    has just been moved to ``active`` status, ideally
    removing/replacing custom location should be allowed. Again, due
    to lack of atomicity in setting image status glance will ignore
    the request and a 409 will be returned.
  * In case where the status of the image is ``active`` and it has
    just been moved to ``deactivated`` status, due to lack of
    atomicity in setting image status, glance may remove/replace
    the location on that image.
  * In case where the status of the image is ``queued`` and it has
    just been moved to ``saving`` status, due to lack of atomicity
    in setting image status, glance may replace the location for
    that image.
  * In case where the status of the image is ``active`` and location
    is attempted to be set on it, and at that point if the image goes
    into ``deleted``, ``pending_delete`` or ``killed`` status, then the
    user must get a HTTP 409 Conflict status. However due to lack of
    atomicity in setting the image status, the location may get updated.

NOTE:
This commit ensures that removal of image locations
is not allowed for an image in any state except ``active`` and
replacement of an image location is not allowed except for ``active``
and ``queued`` images.
Further work is required on the atomicity of glance to accommodate
location updates in cases where the images would be undergoing state
changes.

commit_message:
Revert "Remove the deprecation warning of neutron.db.l3_db"

This reverts commit e14002df6d05ace46f009b122a097f77f8784b25.

Since neutron newton version doesn't have neutron.db.models.l3,
use the old fasion l3_db.

Change-Id: Ifc475cd98a48d5c7dd80606c2fb94097ade8a326

Fix gate issue in stable/newton

Use neutron stable/newton branch for test.

Change-Id: I2f145d54dec541b6af57b25822bb1569640a9760

Update tox install to support constraints and branches

Update tox.ini and tox_install.sh to support constraints and branches.
This also includes an update per [1].

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2016-August/101474.html

Change-Id: I6e126fb6ef9048dd00190bf19e2f3c2e8ce21155
(cherry picked from commit 2bee5d94dfee9d000a2579925b6a2791801ceba8)

Use keystoneauth1 to authenticate with nova

Change-Id: I1f14bf49fd87f1e6b382720e7fa9f72f6bd2734d
(cherry picked from 311c057c088c3aec08aa3a999f9e82f946c2c2d8)

Change-Id: I2f145d54dec541b6af57b25822bb1569640a9760

Add disk-allocation-ration config option

We already support configuring ram and cpu overcommit so
this patch adds the ability to control disk overcommit.

Change-Id: Ib172e8b48cb34de4beb9cec1a277dc43ded36eed
Closes-Bug: 1726346

commit_message:
Run spec validation in linters job instead of py27

The default py27 job ignores the changes to *.rst files. The
linters jobs does not, and it makes more sense to include the
validation we do to the specs in it.

py27 is still left in the list of tox envs so that zuul does not
complain about it missing. It will be removed when we switch py27
to linters in project-config.

Change-Id: Ib14c2a3318dc171be8c8ed8207524ab9774c5ccd

commit_message:
cinder: update key_manager when barbican isn't deployed

Cleanup but use the default key_manager class when barbican isn't
deployed.
Also use the new keymgr_backend parameter, since keymgr_api_class is
deprecated.

commit_message:
Set *_domain_name vars to 'Default' by default

Keystone v2 api's are removed in [1], so it's required
to set user_domain_name and project_domain_name otherwise
all requests fallbacks to keystone v2.0 and fails.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/499783/

Change-Id: If52cd4cea4d3fceb7e272366d20276a209b4dc5b
Closes-Bug: #1723838

commit_message:
upgrades: manage quickstart-centos-base repository

- Add the centos-base repo to overcloud-repo-tripleo-ci.yaml.j2

https://review.openstack.org/501817 changed the way repositories
are handled in upgrades, to allow using the AFS mirrors. However,
it missed the CentOS base repo, which can cause issues when a
package update requires an RPM from the base repo.

- Refactor overcloud-repo-tripleo-ci.yaml.j2 to work on any version.

For now, master is Queens but otherwise we made this script standard to
run on any version.

Co-Authored-By: Javier Pena <jpena@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I634c496672900bb0bbde90dcce0a6c2f3d01d466
Closes-Bug: 1724292

As generic and nested resource providers begin to crystallize and be
exercised, it becomes necessary to be able to express:

- Requesting an allocation of a particular resource class with a
  particular set of traits, and requesting a *different* allocation of
  the *same* resource class with a *different* set of traits.

- Ensuring that requests of certain resources are allocated from the
  same resource provider.

- The ability to spread allocations of effectively-identical resources
  across multiple resource providers in situations of high saturation.

This specification attempts to address these requirements by way of a
numbered syntax on resource and trait keys in flavor extra_specs and the
GET /allocation_candidates Placement API.

commit_message:
Granular Resource Request Syntax

As generic and nested resource providers begin to crystallize and be
exercised, it becomes necessary to be able to express:

- Requesting an allocation of a particular resource class with a
  particular set of traits, and requesting a *different* allocation of
  the *same* resource class with a *different* set of traits.

- Ensuring that requests of certain resources are allocated from the
  same resource provider.

- The ability to spread allocations of effectively-identical resources
  across multiple resource providers in situations of high saturation.

This specification attempts to address these requirements by way of a
numbered syntax on resource and trait keys in flavor extra_specs and the
GET /allocation_candidates Placement API.

APIImpact

blueprint: granular-resource-requests

Change-Id: I49fb16c0e080361e6754edc64754abde3a975e14

commit_message:
Fix gate

Issue 1:
In Zuul v3 the jobs do not run as the 'jenkins' user as they
do in v2. Change trovestack to be more flexible in the username.

Issue 2:
The os-testr 1.0.0 release had a couple of required config changes due
to it's internal usage of stestr.

This change to stestr changed the way tests were discovered by
os-testr and as a result the unit test run was picking up tempest
tests.

Change-Id: If1997302fc954da0c0b80ef846977a1acd0f4a52

commit_message:
Add flag to allow devstack to run on f26 in gate

In Barbican stable branches, we run a gate job on Fedora 26.
devstack needs FORCE=yes flag to run on f26 for Pike and
earlier releases.

Change-Id: I9de812991c4476af4010cd6ecebb8e3c912abf52
(cherry picked from commit 4ad06c11829ca58539ebac71adef0595cea041b7)

Create murano applications package for import

Similar to the murano core library package, adding in
the creation of the io.murano.applications package
to allow it to be imported.

Change-Id: I1c0778fe348893b12180882e48fcc918d09ef47d

commit_message:
Octavia driver to honor Octavia API status codes

Currently the Octavia driver for neutron-lbaas is not honoring Octavia API
status codes. This can lead to a race condition where the status update
thread is behind the actual object status in Octavia.
This updates the driver to raise the appropriate status code to the
neutron API.

Change-Id: I3ec78578c941e4648d1fccfc92b349e3415015e6
Story: 2001257
Task: 5787

commit_message:
Remove jenkins Frozen tests

We're removing all the frozen files in a followup, so can - and have to -

commit_message:
Force trove_auth_url to point to the v3 api URL

After removing keystone API v2, trove requires that
trove_auth_url parameter has the v3 URL. Note that
versionless url is not valid for trove_auth_url so
this patch enforces v3 url even when auth_url is
not versioned.

Additionally, the default value for auth_url parameter
has been updated to point to v3.

Change-Id: I8d0e200958c813101d72e180c6da8343b5fcae6e

'}]
commit_message:
NetApp: Define 'preferred' to False instead of none

Define preferred to false instead of none in the NetApp driver
as setting it to none will trigger a traceback later on because
the database doesn't allow null values to be inserted.
"preferred" export location metadata must be set to true or
false.  warning logging is also added to the SQLAlchemy API
if a none value is used to update the export location metadata.

Change-Id: Ie7420c9286cc42eaa1361eeffe607b9b5b6b3fbd
Closes-Bug: 1703660
(cherry picked from commit 4573826d361b44c367ca54c5d0f7943346666ade)
(cherry picked from commit 0a5d760ed5e49b0aef34ce909d4570585e1b4681)

'}, {'created': '2017-10-24 09:35:14.000000000', 'message': 'Add charm config option for force_raw_images

Since Ocata, backing images are by default converted into raw format
but since Pike a problem with O_DIRECT calls and ZFS backend storage
has presented - i.e., Pike on LXD with ZFS backend storage will result
in an error about image conversion. This config option allows
that default to be changed so that Pike on LXD with ZFS will lauch
instances succesfully.

Closes-Bug: 1710994

Change-Id: Ieba15b44b4b56a356d58c4504dd259fc80e7575d
'}]
commit_message:
Add charm config option for force_raw_images

Since Ocata, backing images are by default converted into raw format
but since Pike a problem with O_DIRECT calls and ZFS backend storage
has presented - i.e., Pike on LXD with ZFS backend storage will result
in an error about image conversion. This config option allows
that default to be changed so that Pike on LXD with ZFS will lauch
instances succesfully.

Closes-Bug: 1710994

Change-Id: Ieba15b44b4b56a356d58c4504dd259fc80e7575d

commit_message:
Install prereqs for undercloud via tripleoclient

Move installation of the packages into the client's
'openstack undercloud deploy' prerequisites phase,
executed as a separate deployment step.

Depends-On: I8064cf96172201bab5ce3546fe2cbccb3f74f827

Change-Id: I4c84023a726e41a96b03ca0851e77705d8fa432d

commit_message:
TLS everywhere: Only generate ssh key if it's not there

The TLS everywhere gate is broken since zuul now generates the ssh key,
so the generation command fails. This makes it optional.

Change-Id: I19cec9f8cf0e4f369e09747d6949a10fcb5aea26

commit_message:
xenapi: cached images should be cleaned up by time

For xenapi driver, there needs to be some way to delete cached
images based on when they were created. add an optional arg to
control delete operation.

Change-Id: I24fc45e989aa951aab55a261fce77f7e3667d988
Closes-bug: 1481689

commit_message:
Temporarily leave launchpad creds for release jobs

The launchpadlib credential setup used by tag-releases to comment on
LP bugs is not yet working as expected. Temporarily stop shredding
and deleting the credential file so that a manually-held node can be
inspected for deeper investigation.

Change-Id: Id4cea87320f89b2c01d94616ee00019c7f69b0e8

This doesn't seem right to me (which probably means I am misunderstanding the situation). If we run up against a resource that is locked by a previous traversal, we're supposed to bail out. The traversal holding the lock will retrigger the latest traversal after it releases the lock. This is designed to guarantee that we only process the resource once for each traversal, and that only the most recent traversal is processed. If we have retries then it appears to me that we lose the guarantees about leaving the resource in the right state (i.e. corresponding to the latest traversal).

What am I missing?"}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2017-09-28 02:57:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

What is expected to happen if the earlier traversal is canceled for some reason? I think I started seeing this issue after the next patch in the series[1]. Though I've not tested, may be we call 'retrigger_check_resource' rather than just returning from there?

> What is expected to happen if the earlier traversal is canceled for some reason?

It looks like we're only retriggering (in CheckResource._handle_resource_failure()) when we get the ResourceFailure or Timeout exceptions, not when we get CancelOperation. That appears to be the bug. 

On success we're retriggering in _initiate_propagate_resource() if the SyncPoints have been deleted, so that's handled. But in any event where we don't try to propagate, we need to retrigger."}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2017-10-04 21:55:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I opened bug 1727007 for this issue.

The other issue mentioned in the comments with timeouts is fixed as bug 1721654.'}]

commit_message:
Add retry for update_templ_id_and_requires

With convergence if a new update for a resource hits a previous
update, where the the first one is stuck with property validations
(normally happens when update is cancelled with rollback), then if
there is no change to the resource, we just update the raw_template
and requires. However, as the resource is already locked, we can't
do that and the stack get's stuck in ROLLBACK_IN_PROGRESS. This
patch adds retry logic for that and also adds a new config option
for number of retries for exception.UpdateInProgress in place of
earlier used 'client_retry_limit'.

Change-Id: I7ee1d7d216aeef3f371cc82f084a4c604845c263
Related-Bug: #1713952

commit_message:
Document new URL format

Add a description of the new URL format for project documentation.
We've been getting a bunch of patches to modify URLs and it's hard
to know which ones are the canonical format since there are redirects
so that both the old and new URLs currently work.

Change-Id: I84136af8315f3421f7d7825fdb7d096f019a6e08

messages: [{'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2017-10-24 14:22:42.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2017-10-24 15:00:15.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2017-10-24 17:38:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Workflow+1 Code-Review+2'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2017-10-24 14:22:42.000000000', 'message': 'do not assume that modules with setup.py are packaged with python jobs

Back in a5e6f88e1 we made the assumption that repos containing puppet
and node.js modules that also have a setup.py were packaged as python
projects. That is not a valid assumption, so remove it. Projects can now

commit_message:
do not assume that modules with setup.py are packaged with python jobs

Back in a5e6f88e1 we made the assumption that repos containing puppet
and node.js modules that also have a setup.py were packaged as python
projects. That is not a valid assumption, so remove it. Projects can now
explicitly select between the packaging type.

Change-Id: Ie98b7677d07acdfaebf3fa725a481491101922eb
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

commit_message:
lxc_cache_preparation: Convert the LXC cache preparation to async task

openSUSE sometimes hangs when running this task. In order to debug this
failure we need to fire up this task and check for it's status on a
separate one. This way, we can avoid Jenkins timeouts and collect logs
properly when that tasks fails to complete within a reasonable amount of
time.

Change-Id: I3acc4436c8b70af097de188b9de2bb9f4e093a09

commit_message:
remove set -e from release scripts to let them accumulate errors

We want the scripts that loop over inputs to do as much work as
possible and then report any errors. Remove set -e so neither script
aborts early.

Change-Id: I719fa69b9a06d98726922ed371e7bbdc0d4c8512
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

commit_message:
Update libvirt volume drivers to use os-brick constants

Most drivers had hard coded protocol strings, and one driver was using
a constant from os-brick that has been deprecated for removal for quite
some time.

This updates all volume drivers to use the current available constants
from os-brick.

Change-Id: I8682804d2299db793c1e4397a07ff67608a8bda6
Closes-bug: #1721993

commit_message:
[placement] add coverage for update of standard resource class

In microversion <= 1.6 it is possible to update a resource class to have
a new name. This is only possible for custom resource classes, but there
was no test to show that the proper 400 was returned when attempting to
change a standard class.

This adds one test to cover it, and in the process changes the name of
a related test to distinguish it from the new one.

Change-Id: I6c665db68de91c0de91c16f7e622f0c7e2f28bc2
Closes-Bug: #1723123

commit_message:
[placement] Confirm that empty resources query causes 400

When a request is made to /resource_providers or /allocation_candidates
with a 'resources' query parameter, and empty value should lead to a
400. This was indeed happening, but there was no gabbi test coverage for
it. This adds tests at both URLs.

Note that because the query parameter is processed by the same code for
both /resource_providers and /allocation_candidates the test duplicates
a code a path, however, that's an implementation detail that we don't
know at the HTTP API layer.

Change-Id: Ia6fc0ac09efc5407a899de4215a2ba0ba0b017fb
Closes-Bug: #1723122

commit_message:
Drop MANIFEST.in - it's not needed by pbr

networking-hyperv already uses PBR:-
setuptools.setup(
	setup_requires=['pbr>=1.8'],
	pbr=True)
This patch removes `MANIFEST.in` file as pbr generates a
sensible manifest from git files and some standard files
and it removes the need for an explicit `MANIFEST.in` file.

Change-Id: I42d39452a012edb2daf07998078ad66c2d52236a

commit_message:
Document scale introspection issues

Related Bugs:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/tripleo/+bug/1672854
https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1425836

Adds a basic warning about trying to introspect many nodes
at once. Perhaps more complete documentation (including a
script to handle issuing specific batch sizes) should be
included in 'Troubleshooting Node Management Failures'?
Or should it get it's own page?

The real issue with this change is that the 'suggested' minimum number
of nodes you need to worry about this might change significnatly with the
attention this bug has been getting we might double of triple this number
by the next release. How do we want to handle the documentation around it then?

Change-Id: I98d7c779c42de42155061555349dd410ae13a3f4

commit_message:
Add a checkbox to disable SNAT on routers

When creating a router, or when setting a gateway on a router - a checkbox
is displayed, which can be unchecked to disable SNAT.

Change-Id: I8bc040018645fe2bde534b7d48e14c17984cc9c4
Closes-bug: #1673076

commit_message:
Change ip_lib network namespace code to use pyroute2

Change network namespace add/delete/list code to use
pyroute2 library instead of calling /sbin/ip.

Also changed all in-tree callers to use the new calls.

Closes-bug: #1717582
Related-bug: #1492714

Change-Id: Id802e77543177fbb95ff15c2c7361172e8824633

commit_message:
Unittest node_info is added with a version_id

This is a follow-up on I422473e888e5e49abb3e598fc2cf2f330620bdcd.  TL;DR:
unittest the version_id is indeed set when a node is added thru
node_info.add_node().

commit_message:
use qos constants from neutron-lib

neutron-lib contains the qos constants now, and neutron is moving to it
in I6ed379b178a2b79fd14385a1d1e87d87eb04bfb9. This patch moves all
references from neutron's qos constants to neutron-lib.

Change-Id: I8cefea2a5e150eba5e84f396a3ae6154cd2c902a

commit_message:
Use the deployment host to download images for tempest

Currently there are two sets of image downloads happening,
which is a common cause of failure in jobs due to the fact
that they're downloaded from a URL outside of OpenStack-CI.

This patch consolidates them into a single single download,
but also uses the deploy host to do the download. The download
gets done to the same location as where the image is cached
in OpenStack-CI, so as long as the SHA256SUM matches, it
will skip the download - making our tests faster and more
reliable.

As part of this, some legacy and unnecessary variables have
been removed. Also, we were uploading the same image twice
into Glance which is unnecessary. Instead we re-use the same
image ID twice in the tempest configuration.

Change-Id: I8d0afd08f6c80594d69b8d711261ae6365fad917
(cherry picked from commit 5c307f9b20df6959a8953951f3da0f474e3288c3)

commit_message:
trunk: Fix init_handler() agent parameter

Commit 40866acd02a5ecd7fc6705578a82ea79946549a2 stopped passing agent
object as parameter as it's already referenced by `trigger' parameter.
This leads to an error during notify_after_init() in agents' code and
hence trunk handlers are never initialized. This patch replaces `agent'
reference with `trigger' to correctly initialize handlers.

Change-Id: I808980553056b9fec4e2700c1d5440e42091afbf
Closes-bug: #1722967

commit_message:
Remove explicit lockdown of flake8

The hacking version should require the proper dep
of flake8, which includes pep8 and pyflakes.

Change-Id: Ia55a7f355e4ddd190d5bb66491ba8f76b0912a3b

commit_message:
iptables: don't log lock error if we haven't passed -w

In this case, it's an expected error, and we retry again with -w.

Related-Bug: #1712185
Change-Id: I97bf3032b5cebcbce51a3b3de6cb128ca342bd87

commit_message:
Add missing checks for failed cases in snat ping

Every time we change the security group, the exception list is lost, so
when we check it, the past errors are lost.
Added checking to show failed tests.

Change-Id: I7c3c46152a07706e818dbe1ee20235ad574ef4b2

commit_message:
Use the attribute instead of method to get platform_family

Other cookbooks have switched to using the node attribute
https://github.com/openstack/cookbook-openstack-common/blob/master/attributes/default.rb#L292
Using platform_family breaks with chef-client 13.x

Closes-Bug: #1724987

Change-Id: I02fcb5d9403210d913e85487de5ef0dae6066bdc

I would like to see the same interface for creating a port with fixed IP as https://review.openstack.org/325104 does.
"nova interface-attach" operation supports passing port-id.
The combination of net-id and fixed-ip is a convenient way, but we can get the full feature by passing 'port-id'.

In addition we can potentially share the code with https://review.openstack.org/325104 .

Thought?'}, {'account_id': 17172, 'date': '2016-08-05 06:01:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 12: Workflow-1

@Akihiro, I agree with you. If possible, these should be a same interface.
How about below? A user select a way to specify and fields displayed depend on a user's action.  

The case of Attach Interface
  A user select a way to specify(Choice Fields)
   - net_id
   - port
  If a user choose 'net_id', fields to specify 'net_id' and 'fixed_ip(optional)' will appear.
  And if a user choose 'port', a choice field to select a port will appear.

The case of Create Port
  A user select a way to specify(Choice Fields)
   - No specify
   - subnet
   - fixed_ip
  If a user choose 'No specify', any fields are not shown.
  If a user choose 'subnet', only fields 'subnet' will appear. 
  If a user choose 'fixed_ip', only field 'fixed_ip' will appear. 

Thank you!"}, {'account_id': 17172, 'date': '2016-08-05 11:41:09.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 13.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2016-08-05 13:13:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13: Verified+1

commit_message:
Support fixed ip address when attaching interface

At the moment, when a user attaches an interface to
an instance, only a network can be specified.
But actually in nova, it is supported to specify a
fixed IP address or a port.
This patch will support these ways.

Change-Id: I3535024a4f6ffd26b508f5e9afb25232202e1e02
Closes-Bug: #1595913

commit_message:
Add OpenStack-Ansible metadata

We need to add openstack ansible information in the role
metadata to be able to track role maturity. With it,
we can create a role maturity table and take decisions about
role deprecations.

Change-Id: I890bfe2c7e23570ccd0d44f08e8a5667b46b60af

commit_message:
Delay rpc initialization until config is available

When being run within __init__() the rpc.init() call sees an empty
config, leading to errors when doing RPC call later. So we move it to a
later stage where we have read the config and can setup RPC properly.

Change-Id: I195b57bf9c001883764dc160ced40272c5eb4fd3
Closes-Bug: 1651576
(cherry picked from commit 30e037063d714e2ce9792bb462d01ba8bf2a5c98)

commit_message:
Move the idmapshift binary into privsep.

I can't see any evidence that anyone else uses our nova-idmapshift
binary, and it adds a lot of complexity (flags we never call for
example). Move the code we do actually use into the privsep
directory and simplify our calls to it. Remove the extra binary
from our install and documentation.

Change-Id: Ibce28d20d166da154833376cf51f1877b829925e

commit_message:
fix nova accepting invalid availability zone name with ':'

Nova has a legacy hack to allow admins to specify hosts via an
availability zone using az:host:node. That means ':' cannot be
included in the name of an availability zone itself.

However, the aggregate API accepts requests which have
availability zone names including ':'.

This patch checks the availabilty zone name when aggregate is
created or updated and raises an error if it contains ':'.

Conflicts:
      api-ref/source/parameters.yaml

NOTE(mriedem): The conflict in the api-ref docs is due to not
having change f657efcdc59e6b80f5e96beb7f9fdc59d8aadbec in Pike.

Change-Id: I9b0d8e8d4b3ab2cb3d578c22fa259e0e7c0d325b
Closes-Bug: #1695861
(cherry picked from commit 38b25397e805dcf7a995666049713304fe4f1af1)

commit_message:
Initial Zuul v3 role jobs

This patch implements an initial set of jobs intended to match
the current job execution method. It does not intend to improve
how the jobs are executed - only to replicate what is currently
in openstack-infra/openstack-zuul-jobs and provide the platform
to iterate on.

Change-Id: I03fc09f9eeb322c9977a2e89a7902613a8b699f4

If I'm understanding 91dcdb5c correctly, this will result in a different device name which is a bad thing. I'd like BobBall or someone else with Xen-fu to take a look at this"}, {'account_id': 6735, 'date': '2017-06-13 14:22:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I get the argument that this should be for fully configured VMs (see discussion on bug) - but there are often cases where you can't use the PV drivers or they are not functional.  For example, nested Xen can't support the PV drivers and in this case IDE is definitely the right bus, and Windows guests don't support the xen bus until the PV drivers are installed, so *must* start with the IDE bus.
IDE is the safe bus until the management layer knows that the drivers are installed in-guest.

I don't really know what the right answer is here; I'd like input from Anthony.
It feels like some of the logic that exists in other toolstacks around querying the guest at runtime for support of a particular bus is the "right" answer as far as the hypervisor is concerned, but that might not make sense for Nova.'}, {'account_id': 13671, 'date': '2017-06-13 15:17:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 14620, 'date': '2017-06-16 14:46:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I still don't think it is a good idee to have something else than "ide" as default for HVM guests.

With Xen (without OpenStack), when you configure a guest to have an "hda" (so IDE disk) you also get a PV disk. When the guest driver is ready, it simply ask to the IDE disks to be unplug and start using the PV disk. But before that, there is a firmware/BIOS that is going to load the guest OS from disk and this BIOS have only support for IDE.

So my guess with OpenStack with a default to "xen" is that a guest will not be able to boot if you forget to set the metadata for the boot disk.

I think I need to find some time to find out what OpenStack is doing with HVM guests.'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2017-10-24 15:28:51.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

Based on responses from Bob and Anthony, and those were several months ago now, I'm going to abandon this since it's stuck."}]

commit_message:
Set default disk bus for libvirt+Xen HVM to "xen"

QEMU/KVM guests have "virtio" as default disk bus for disk which is
QEMU analog of "xen" bus for XEN. So bring to same defaults.
User still able to use other buses by metadata.

Change-Id: I168d903f15d2761dc82d60d277f41e0b4d9cc82d
Closes-Bug: 1655662

[{'created': '2017-03-21 02:47:02.000000000', 'message': 'Nova client should retry with Retry-After value

If a request fails but the response contains a "Retry-After",
the nova client should wait the amount of time and then retry.
Nova client should report a warning to user and continue with
retry, so that user can cancel the operation if not interested
in retry. The value in "Retry-After" header will be in seconds
or GMT value, client should handle both the cases.

How many times client should retry will be controlled by user
through "--retries" argument to nova api example,
$ nova --retries 3 availability-zone-list

If request was not sucessful within the retries, client should
raise the exception.

commit_message:
Nova client should retry with Retry-After value

If a request fails but the response contains a "Retry-After",
the nova client should wait the amount of time and then retry.
Nova client should report a warning to user and continue with
retry, so that user can cancel the operation if not interested
in retry. The value in "Retry-After" header will be in seconds
or GMT value, client should handle both the cases.

If request was not sucessful within the retries, client should
raise the exception.

Change-Id: Ibbbe9899c5cf25bd5b2d45307ad2ec00932ecfe4
Partial-Bug: #1263069

(3 comments)

I think this won't fly for both technical and social reasons. This is not impossible, but we need to approach this problem properly. It's not something to be solved on TripleO level. Until then, I don't want to commit to this proposal, at least for Ironic (both in under and overcloud).

Specific problems with this proposal are:

0. It's purely Red Hat specific. It's not a huge deal for a Red Hat only project, but it will count when we come upstream with e.g. upgrade problems. We will have to be able to answer questions like "why not Mitaka->Pike", "why not N-2 -> N", etc.

1. It assumes that upgrades are limited to updating the code, changing configuration and running dbsync. This is not true. Upgrades can involve operations on running services of a particular release. E.g. Ironic upgrade will require running periodic tasks in nova-compute. If nothing changes, this periodic tasks will only exist in Pike. If you never ran Pike, you're in trouble. This is not a unique situation, I'm pretty sure. Which leads to the next problem

2. We need upstream buy-in. I touched upon this already, but I want to re-emphasize this critical issue. If it's not something the whole OpenStack more or less agrees on, you can't expect any help when a service breaks such upgrade. And asking upstream will mean..

3. We need CI testing for such upgrades. Which is barely possible, because a) Newton is going EOL very soon, before we even release Queens, b) stable teams are understaffed, c) the infra team and infra resources are lacking.

Before we solve these problems, I can't see us committing to such a challenge.'}, {'account_id': 6133, 'date': '2017-09-05 10:28:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(6 comments)'}, {'account_id': 10135, 'date': '2017-09-05 12:36:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

> (3 comments)
 > 
 > I think this won't fly for both technical and social reasons. This
 > is not impossible, but we need to approach this problem properly.
 > It's not something to be solved on TripleO level. Until then, I
 > don't want to commit to this proposal, at least for Ironic (both in
 > under and overcloud).
 > 
 > Specific problems with this proposal are:
 > 
 > 0. It's purely Red Hat specific. It's not a huge deal for a Red Hat
 > only project, but it will count when we come upstream with e.g.
 > upgrade problems. We will have to be able to answer questions like
 > "why not Mitaka->Pike", "why not N-2 -> N", etc.

I can't say that I understand your concern here. The proposal is to stick with the currently supported N to N+1 jumps for upgrades and our plan to start with N to N+3 doesn't rule out allow N to N+2 in the future. Limiting this initial effort to N to N+3 also helps narrow down our requirements on CI for the time being.

 > 1. It assumes that upgrades are limited to updating the code,
 > changing configuration and running dbsync. This is not true.
 > Upgrades can involve operations on running services of a particular
 > release. E.g. Ironic upgrade will require running periodic tasks in
 > nova-compute. If nothing changes, this periodic tasks will only
 > exist in Pike. If you never ran Pike, you're in trouble. This is
 > not a unique situation, I'm pretty sure. Which leads to the next
 > problem

Thanks for the heads up! FWIW Ironic in the overcloud wasn't part of our original PoC and we didn't see this behaviour with any other components.

Which specific periodic task does Ironic need n-cpu to run? Do we have docs highlighting this as a post upgrade requirement? I couldn't find any but I'm sure I've missed something.

I would think this could be avoided via a `nova-manage` command to force this through without n-cpu running as we do with cellsv2 etc but I'd be happy to be corrected.

 > 2. We need upstream buy-in. I touched upon this already, but I want
 > to re-emphasize this critical issue. If it's not something the
 > whole OpenStack more or less agrees on, you can't expect any help
 > when a service breaks such upgrade. And asking upstream will mean..

I fully agree, that's why I'm chairing the skip level upgrades room at the PTG next week :

https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/queens-PTG-skip-level-upgrades

That said the work outlined in this spec is a retrospective effort on our part, targeting upgrades between the now EOL'd Newton release and Queens, where we can't and don't expect the community to change in terms of stable lifecycles and support for upgrades. Going forward from Queens this could change but IMHO is separate to this spec and work for the time being.

 > 3. We need CI testing for such upgrades. Which is barely possible,
 > because a) Newton is going EOL very soon, before we even release
 > Queens, b) stable teams are understaffed, c) the infra team and
 > infra resources are lacking.

Agreed, to that point we would need RDO CI to test Newton to Queens, thus negating the impact on the upstream stable and infra teams.'}, {'account_id': 10135, 'date': '2017-09-05 12:57:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(14 comments)'}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2017-09-05 13:15:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Lee, I'm referring to this change: https://github.com/openstack/nova/commit/8e77c475e1eb48703314e1b98bc9cb491027064d. This task runs in Pike, and the plan is to remove it in Queens. Thus, Newton->Queens upgrade will miss it.

If the plan is to only skip-level upgrade the core services, let's please indicate it in the spec. If the plan is to support all services, we need to make more work making sure it's possible (and won't break in Queens).

As to the social aspect, I'm thinking of the following situation. A project (say, Nova) breaks N-3 -> N upgrade. You come to them, and they refuse to fix it, because $many_reasons. Your next actions?"}, {'account_id': 10135, 'date': '2017-09-05 13:56:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

> Lee, I'm referring to this change: https://github.com/openstack/nova/commit/8e77c475e1eb48703314e1b98bc9cb491027064d.
 > This task runs in Pike, and the plan is to remove it in Queens.
 > Thus, Newton->Queens upgrade will miss it.
 
Thanks, so this is possibly something we would need to stand n-cpu and n-cond up for to allow it to run while we are on Pike. That's possible with the steps approach outlined in the spec (step 4) but we would need to be define verification and cleanup tasks as well. I'll add more on this to the spec now as there could well be other projects where this is also required.

 > If the plan is to only skip-level upgrade the core services, let's
 > please indicate it in the spec. If the plan is to support all
 > services, we need to make more work making sure it's possible (and
 > won't break in Queens).
 
Yes it's all possible overcloud services and I agree there's more work required here.

 > As to the social aspect, I'm thinking of the following situation. A
 > project (say, Nova) breaks N-3 -> N upgrade. You come to them, and
 > they refuse to fix it, because $many_reasons. Your next actions?

Again to highlight that this is N-3 to N via N-3 to N-2, N-2 to N-1 and N-1 to N, so if a step in this process is broken the projects should be willing to help fix the issue unless the release has already hit EOL."}, {'account_id': 21908, 'date': '2017-09-05 14:31:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Introduce fast-forward upgrades

Fast-forward upgrades are upgrades that move an environment from release
`N` to `N+X` in a single step, where `X` is greater than `1` and  for
fast forward upgrades is typically `3`. This spec outlines how such
upgrades can be orchestrated by TripleO between the Newton and Queens
releases.

Change-Id: I7a422f2355b63dde788207d6ff388f6bee594b33

commit_message:
Initial Zuul v3 role jobs

This patch implements an initial set of jobs intended to match
the current job execution method. It does not intend to improve
how the jobs are executed - only to replicate what is currently
in openstack-infra/openstack-zuul-jobs and provide the platform
to iterate on.

Change-Id: Ia6ccc812b1fcaa7b0b8ea687ca7be7eab850aa12

commit_message:
Initial Zuul v3 role jobs

This patch implements an initial set of jobs intended to match
the current job execution method. It does not intend to improve
how the jobs are executed - only to replicate what is currently
in openstack-infra/openstack-zuul-jobs and provide the platform
to iterate on.

Change-Id: I18ddfbcbef6c6f306d4f2fc0f7771d2600c397ce

commit_message:
Logrotate not restarting rsyslog

logrotate is not sending HUP signal to rsyslog because of invalid
command in postrotate/endscript block. Fixed the command to reload
the rsyslog after the logs are rotated.

Change-Id: Ia1fa205e6f20c212841109c914a8c7e2d379a48b
(cherry picked from commit c63290a0a471b7e4594df11a8049e92b8302f24f)
(cherry picked from commit 236d6f03bb8267dc908318e1a831ce9b61667ffd)

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-10-23 22:26:58.000000000', 'message': 'Ensure upgrade installs correct configs

When we do an openstack upgrade we must ensure that
release version dependant decisions are made at the
right time. In this patch we ensure that we choose
configs after the target release packages have been
installed so as to be sure that e.g. when upgrading
from Newton to Ocata the apache2 wsgi conf is
installed for the cinder-api.

Change-Id: I9414940535406c7c7491636839a328df1ac9235b
Closes-Bug: 1726527
'}]
commit_message:
Ensure upgrade installs correct configs

When we do an openstack upgrade we must ensure that
release version dependant decisions are made at the
right time. In this patch we ensure that we choose
configs after the target release packages have been
installed so as to be sure that e.g. when upgrading
from Newton to Ocata the apache2 wsgi conf is
installed for the cinder-api.

Change-Id: I9414940535406c7c7491636839a328df1ac9235b
Closes-Bug: 1726527

commit_message:
tripleo-messaging specification

This specification is to allow for the separation of RPC and
Notify messaging backends. Builds upon capabilities that were
added in the Pike release.

Change-Id: I07ed146d86698ecbb12324cea534aef7ff163628

commit_message:
tripleo-ovs-hw-offload

Adding Spec file for adding ovs-hw_offload functionality to tripleo.

This functionality is already available from the Pike release in
Open Stack.

Herein this specification tries to capture what we need to do to
get this functionality within tripleo

commit_message:
Release ironic 6.3.0 for Newton

Please see the commit message of https://review.openstack.org/#/c/468925/
for the sad story on how we ended up bumping minor version on a stable
brunch. TL;DR the minimum requirements for one vendor was broken and
never worked in reality. Thus, the expected practical impact of the
version change is quite small.

Change-Id: I3e212741f8973b2aa95982a7fc9ebe6dcbc3d9dc

commit_message:
[WIP][hooks] Move processing results to HookExecutor

The logic of processing results should be moved outside HookTrigger,
so we can ensure that the results have the right format.

Change-Id: Ib6c922e5b4e6aa99837d08c83dfffe0ac1277999

commit_message:
Initial Zuul v3 role jobs

This patch implements an initial set of jobs intended to match
the current job execution method. It does not intend to improve
how the jobs are executed - only to replicate what is currently
in openstack-infra/openstack-zuul-jobs and provide the platform
to iterate on.

Change-Id: Ib04a91c09f89c4e2d29f6610ac2f7f214ec74804

commit_message:
Implement network availability zone column in network list

If the 'network_availability_zone'-extension is enabled, this patch adds a
column in the Networks-table named 'Availability Zones'.

Change-Id: Iea2bac351b922a0d267c4a55e0d74f6c2639d967
Partial-Bug: #1725617

commit_message:
Initial Zuul v3 role jobs

This patch implements an initial set of jobs intended to match
the current job execution method. It does not intend to improve
how the jobs are executed - only to replicate what is currently
in openstack-infra/openstack-zuul-jobs and provide the platform
to iterate on.

Change-Id: Ia0e9f155a8aeb3a6ea948a23d7de745d6f3ae6b6

commit_message:
Cap compute floating IPs tests

Nova removed the os-floating-ips endpoint in 2.36 and deprecated the
associate and disassociate fip APIs in 2.44. To reflect this, this
patch caps the corresponding tempest tests to 2.35 and 2.43.

This patch also refactors some of the housekeeping classmethods in all
floating IPs tests to reduce code duplication.

Change-Id: Ic0eb61e6bdd427c320aef76a17da157d0d9524de

commit_message:
Initial Zuul v3 role jobs

This patch implements an initial set of jobs intended to match
the current job execution method. It does not intend to improve
how the jobs are executed - only to replicate what is currently
in openstack-infra/openstack-zuul-jobs and provide the platform
to iterate on.

Change-Id: I85779a1f3a1a3243cd7143e915d204a84537c2cd

commit_message:
Add missing hostnames to fluentd log messages

- Sets the hostname on rabbitmq and mariadb log messages
  according to the local host.
- Sets the hostname on syslog log messages by extracting it
  from the syslog message. In many cases this will be the
  same as the local host, but it may also be a remote host.

Closes-Bug: #1726596
Change-Id: I3093215720662c158d1417e15bac1bbaec3c4ab7

commit_message:
Various fixes to get tox and verification working

The charm-helpers project moved from launchpad to github.
Create a copyright file to work around pep8 warning.
Fix keystone.service_catalog.url_for calls to use 'interface'
parameter versus 'endpoint_type'.
Add .stestr to .gitignore file.

Change-Id: I215b09b97e4cd9ebbad5dcb41a03d0c09dcfd9ef
